var tafsirData_6 = {
  1: {
    "All praise is for Allah Who created the heavens and the earth": "All gratitude and praise belong exclusively to Allah, the One who brought into existence the entire universe—the skies above with all their stars and celestial bodies, and the earth below with all its features. This establishes that Allah alone deserves worship because He alone is the Creator. When someone builds something magnificent, they deserve recognition. Allah built everything, so all praise naturally belongs to Him. This opening reminds us that creation itself is proof of a Creator worthy of all thanks.",
    "and made darkness and light": "Allah is the One who created the contrast between darkness and light—both the physical darkness of night and brightness of day, as well as the metaphorical darkness of ignorance and light of guidance. Everything operates by His design. Light allows us to see, work, and thrive, while darkness gives us rest. Both are blessings, and both are under Allah's control. This shows His complete mastery over all aspects of existence.",
    "Yet the disbelievers set up equals to their Lord ˹in worship˺": "Despite all these clear signs of Allah's power and creative authority, those who reject faith still assign partners to Him in worship. They worship idols, other beings, or even their own desires alongside Allah. This is deeply illogical—how can anyone who did not create anything be considered equal to the One who created everything? It is like thanking a stranger for a gift your own father gave you. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was asked about the greatest sin, and he said it was to set up rivals with Allah though He alone created you (Bukhari). This verse highlights the absurdity of polytheism in light of Allah's obvious creative power."
  },
  2: {
    "He is the One Who created you from clay": "Allah created the father of humanity, Adam (peace be upon him), from clay—from the earth itself. This is a reminder of our humble origins. No matter how proud or arrogant a person becomes, they should remember they come from dust and will return to dust. This also connects all human beings to a common origin, reminding us of our equality before our Creator. The Quran mentions in another place that Allah created Adam from sounding clay, from mud molded into shape (15:26).",
    "then appointed a term ˹for your death˺": "Allah has decreed for every person a specific lifespan—the exact moment when their life in this world will end. No one can delay it or advance it by even a moment. This appointed term is known to Allah alone. It reminds us that life is temporary and we should use our time wisely. Every breath we take brings us closer to that appointed time.",
    "and another known only to Him ˹for your resurrection˺": "Beyond the term of death, there is another appointed time—the Day of Resurrection—which is known only to Allah. No angel, no prophet, no human knows exactly when the world will end and all souls will be raised again for judgment. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was asked about the Hour, and he said the one being asked knows no more than the questioner (Bukhari). This emphasizes Allah's exclusive knowledge of the unseen.",
    "—yet you continue to doubt!": "Despite all these clear signs of Allah's power—creating the universe, creating you, controlling life and death—people still have doubts about His existence, His oneness, or the reality of resurrection. This is an expression of amazement at human stubbornness. When someone creates you and controls every aspect of your existence, how can you doubt their power to bring you back to life? It is like doubting that an artist who painted a masterpiece could repaint it again."
  },
  3: {
    "He is the Only True God in the heavens and the earth": "Allah alone is the true deity deserving of worship throughout the entire creation—in the heavens and on the earth. There is no place where another god exists or has any power. His divinity and authority extend everywhere without limitation. This negates the idea that different gods control different realms or regions. Allah's sovereignty is complete and universal.",
    "He knows whatever you conceal and whatever you reveal": "Allah has complete knowledge of everything—both what you hide in your hearts and what you express openly. Your secret thoughts, hidden intentions, private conversations, and inner feelings are all known to Him. Nothing escapes His awareness. This should make a believer conscious of their inner state, not just their outward actions. You might fool people with a good appearance while harboring bad intentions, but Allah sees through everything.",
    "and knows whatever you do": "Beyond your thoughts and words, Allah also knows every action you perform—whether done publicly or privately, whether big or small. Every deed is recorded and will be presented on the Day of Judgment. This comprehensive knowledge of Allah should inspire both hope and caution: hope that He sees your good deeds even when no one else notices, and caution that He also sees your sins even when you think no one is watching."
  },
  4: {
    "Whenever a sign comes to them from their Lord, they turn away from it": "Every time a proof, miracle, or evidence of Allah's truth reaches these disbelievers, they deliberately turn their backs on it. They do not pause to reflect or consider its meaning. Whether it is a verse of the Quran, a natural phenomenon pointing to Allah, or a logical argument proving His existence—they refuse to engage with it honestly. This is not because the signs are unclear, but because their hearts are unwilling to accept. It is like someone closing their eyes and claiming they cannot see the sun. The problem is not with the sun's brightness but with their refusal to look."
  },
  5: {
    "They have indeed rejected the truth when it came to them": "These people did not reject the message because it was unclear or unproven. They rejected it despite knowing it was the truth. The Quran, the Prophet's character, and all the evidence were right before them, yet they chose denial. This is the height of injustice—to recognize truth and still refuse it out of arrogance, jealousy, or attachment to worldly interests.",
    "so they will soon face the consequences of their ridicule": "Those who mocked the message, the Prophet, and the believers will eventually face the reality of what they laughed at. What they considered impossible—resurrection, judgment, paradise, and hellfire—will become their lived experience. The word \"soon\" indicates that from Allah's perspective, the Day of Judgment is near, even if it seems far to us. This is both a warning and a promise: no mockery of the truth goes unanswered."
  },
  6: {
    "Have they not seen how many ˹disbelieving˺ peoples We destroyed before them?": "This is a call to reflect on history. Many powerful nations existed before the Arabs of Makkah—nations that denied their messengers and were subsequently destroyed. The ruins of 'Ad, Thamud, the people of Lot, and Pharaoh's Egypt were known to them through travel and oral tradition. History is meant to be a teacher, but only for those willing to learn.",
    "We had made them more established in the land than you": "These previous nations were far more powerful, wealthy, and technologically advanced than the Quraysh. They had stronger kingdoms, greater armies, and more resources. Yet all their power could not save them when Allah's punishment came. This should humble anyone who feels secure because of their worldly strength. If nations mightier than you were destroyed, what makes you think you are immune?",
    "We sent down abundant rain for them and made rivers flow at their feet": "Allah blessed these nations with plentiful resources—rain that made their lands fertile and rivers that provided water, transportation, and prosperity. These were signs of Allah's favor and should have led them to gratitude and obedience. Instead, they became arrogant and took these blessings for granted, forgetting the One who provided them.",
    "Then We destroyed them for their sins and replaced them with other peoples": "Despite all their blessings, when these nations persisted in sin and rejection of their messengers, Allah destroyed them. Their civilizations collapsed, and new peoples took their place. This is a powerful reminder that no nation is permanent. When a people abandon gratitude to Allah and persist in wrongdoing, they are eventually replaced. The Quran states elsewhere: If you turn away, He will replace you with another people, and they will not be like you (47:38)."
  },
  7: {
    "Had We sent down to you ˹O Prophet˺ a revelation in writing and they were to touch it with their own hands": "Even if Allah had sent down a physical book from the sky—something they could see descending and touch with their own hands, leaving no room for doubt about its miraculous origin—these stubborn disbelievers would still refuse to believe.",
    "the disbelievers would still have said, \"This is nothing but pure magic!\"": "They would dismiss even such an undeniable miracle as mere magic or illusion. This shows that their rejection is not based on lack of evidence but on an unwillingness to accept the truth. Their hearts are sealed by arrogance and stubbornness. No amount of proof will convince someone who has already decided not to believe. This is why faith is ultimately a matter of the heart, not just the mind. The Prophet (peace be upon him) faced this constantly—people demanding miracles while ignoring the greatest miracle, the Quran, which was right before them."
  },
  8: {
    "They say, \"Why has no ˹visible˺ angel come with him?\"": "The disbelievers demanded that an angel visibly descend to confirm Muhammad's prophethood. They thought this would be proof they could not deny. But this demand came from a place of arrogance, not sincere seeking. They were essentially saying that a human messenger was not good enough for them.",
    "Had We sent down an angel, the matter would have certainly been settled ˹at once˺": "If Allah had sent a visible angel, and the disbelievers still rejected the message, then judgment would be immediate and final. There would be no more time for repentance or consideration. When angels come with punishment, there are no second chances.",
    "and they would have never been given more time ˹to repent˺": "The delay in sending an angel is actually a mercy. It gives people time to reflect, reconsider, and turn back to Allah. If their demand was granted and they still rejected, destruction would be immediate. Allah, in His wisdom and mercy, gives humanity time and opportunity to find guidance. This life is a test, and part of that test is believing without seeing everything one demands to see."
  },
  9: {
    "And if We had sent an angel, We would have certainly made it ˹assume the form of˺ a man": "Even if Allah had sent an angel as a messenger, that angel would have appeared in human form. Angels in their true form are beings of immense light and power that humans cannot bear to see. When the Angel Jibreel (Gabriel) appeared to the Prophet in his true form, it filled the entire horizon. For regular communication with humanity, angels take human form.",
    "—leaving them more confused than they already are": "If an angel came in human form, the disbelievers would face the same confusion they created for themselves with human prophets. They would say, \"This is just a man like us,\" the same objection they raised against Muhammad (peace be upon him). So their demand for an angel would not actually solve their problem of disbelief—it would only add to their confusion. The real issue is not the form of the messenger but the condition of their hearts."
  },
  10: {
    "˹Other˺ messengers had already been ridiculed before you ˹O Prophet˺": "This verse consoles the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) by reminding him that he is not alone in facing mockery. Many messengers before him—Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and others—were also ridiculed by their people. This is a pattern throughout history: those who bring truth are often mocked by those who reject it. The Prophet should not be disheartened because this opposition is part of the test that all messengers faced.",
    "but those who mocked them were overtaken by what they used to ridicule": "The very punishment and consequences that the mockers laughed at eventually came upon them. When Noah warned of a flood, they laughed—until the flood came. When Lot warned of destruction, they mocked—until stones rained down. The thing they thought was a joke became their reality. This is both a warning to current disbelievers and comfort to the Prophet and believers: mockery of truth never goes unanswered."
  },
  11: {
    "Say, \"Travel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers.\"": "The Prophet is commanded to invite people to travel and observe the ruins of previous civilizations. The remains of destroyed nations—like the people of 'Ad in Yemen, Thamud in Madain Saleh, Sodom and Gomorrah near the Dead Sea, and Pharaoh's monuments in Egypt—serve as physical evidence of Allah's punishment upon those who denied His messengers. This is not ancient mythology but observable history. Travel and reflection can open the heart to lessons that mere words might not convey. Seeing the ruins of once-mighty civilizations humbles the arrogant and warns the heedless."
  },
  12: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"To whom belongs everything in the heavens and the earth?\" Say, \"To Allah!\"": "This is a rhetorical question designed to make people acknowledge an obvious truth. Everything in existence—every star, planet, mountain, ocean, creature, and atom—belongs to Allah. He created it all, He sustains it all, and He owns it all. Even the disbelievers, when pressed, would acknowledge that the universe must have a Creator and Owner. This ownership is the foundation of why only Allah deserves worship.",
    "He has taken upon Himself to be Merciful": "Out of His infinite grace, Allah has made mercy a binding attribute upon Himself. This is not because anyone forced Him or because He owes creation anything—it is His choice. This is immensely comforting: the All-Powerful, the Owner of everything, has chosen to be merciful to His creation. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah divided mercy into one hundred parts, kept ninety-nine with Himself, and sent down one part to earth, and from that one part comes all the compassion creatures show to one another (Bukhari and Muslim).",
    "He will certainly gather ˹all of˺ you together for the Day of Judgment—about which there is no doubt": "Allah will definitely resurrect all of humanity for the Day of Judgment. This is a certainty, not a possibility. The resurrection will happen, and every soul will stand before Allah for accounting. There is no escaping this appointment, and there should be no doubt about it. The Quran repeatedly emphasizes this to counter those who denied the afterlife.",
    "But those who have ruined themselves will never believe": "Those who have destroyed their own souls through persistent disbelief and sin will not accept this truth. Their ruin is self-inflicted—Allah gave them guidance, evidence, and time, but they chose to reject it. By consistently turning away from truth, they have damaged their own capacity to believe. This is a tragic state: being offered salvation but refusing to take it."
  },
  13: {
    "To Him belongs whatever exists in the day and night": "Everything that dwells, moves, rests, or operates during the day and the night belongs to Allah. This includes all creatures that are active by day and those that emerge at night. It includes all human activities, all natural processes, and all events—nothing happens outside His ownership and control. Day and night themselves are signs of His power, and everything within them is under His authority.",
    "And He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing": "Allah hears every sound—every prayer, every whisper, every secret conversation, even the thoughts that never become words. And He knows everything—past, present, and future; what is apparent and what is hidden. These attributes mean that nothing escapes Allah's awareness. Your prayers are heard, your struggles are known, and your sincerity is recognized. This is both comforting for believers and a warning for those who think they can hide their wrongdoing."
  },
  14: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Will I take any guardian other than Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth": "The Prophet is commanded to declare that he will never take any protector, helper, or object of worship besides Allah—the One who originated the heavens and earth from nothing. The word \"Originator\" (Fatir) means He created without any prior model or material. He brought everything into existence by His will alone. How could anyone choose a lesser protector when the Creator of everything is available?",
    "Who provides for all and is not in need of provision?\"": "Allah feeds and sustains all creation, yet He Himself needs nothing from anyone. He gives but never needs to receive. He provides for the ant in its hole and the whale in the ocean, yet requires no sustenance Himself. This complete self-sufficiency combined with His generosity makes Him the only logical choice for guardianship and worship. Any other supposed god would itself need provision, making it unworthy of worship.",
    "Say, \"I have been commanded to be the first to submit and not be one of the polytheists.\"": "The Prophet declares that he has been commanded by Allah to be the foremost in submission (Islam) among his people and to completely avoid polytheism. This is the Prophet leading by example—he is not asking others to do what he himself does not do. He is the first to submit, the most devoted in worship, and the most careful to avoid associating anything with Allah."
  },
  15: {
    "Say, \"I truly fear—if I were to disobey my Lord—the torment of a tremendous Day.\"": "The Prophet expresses genuine fear of disobeying Allah and facing punishment on the Day of Judgment. If the Prophet himself—the most beloved to Allah—expresses such fear, how much more should ordinary people be concerned about their obedience? This shows that true faith includes healthy fear of Allah's displeasure. The \"tremendous Day\" refers to the Day of Judgment, whose horrors are beyond imagination. This fear is not paralyzing but motivating—it drives the believer toward obedience and away from sin."
  },
  16: {
    "Whoever is spared the torment of that Day will have certainly been shown Allah's mercy": "On the Day of Judgment, anyone who is protected from the punishment has received Allah's mercy. Being saved from hellfire is not something anyone earns through their deeds alone—it is ultimately Allah's mercy that saves. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that no one will enter Paradise by their deeds alone, and when asked \"Not even you?\" he replied \"Not even me, unless Allah covers me with His mercy\" (Bukhari).",
    "And that is the absolute triumph": "Being saved from the torment of that Day is the ultimate success—the clear, manifest, undeniable victory. All worldly successes pale in comparison. A person might have wealth, fame, and power in this world but face eternal punishment in the next—that is ultimate failure. Conversely, someone might struggle in this world but be saved on that Day—that is true success. This verse redefines what winning really means."
  },
  17: {
    "If Allah touches you with harm, none can undo it except Him": "When Allah decrees hardship, illness, loss, or any difficulty for someone, no power in existence can remove it except Allah Himself. No doctor, no medicine, no wealth, no influential person can lift what Allah has decreed. This does not mean we should not seek help through means—we should—but we must understand that the means only work by Allah's permission. This teaches complete reliance on Allah (tawakkul) especially during difficulties.",
    "And if He touches you with a blessing, He is Most Capable of everything": "Similarly, when Allah bestows good—health, wealth, happiness, success—it is from Him, and He has unlimited power to give more. His capacity for good is infinite. This encourages the believer to turn to Allah for all needs, knowing that His power has no limits. Whether in hardship or ease, the direction should always be toward Allah. He can turn poverty into wealth, sickness into health, and despair into hope."
  },
  18: {
    "He reigns supreme over His creation": "Allah is Al-Qahir—the Irresistible, the Dominant, the One who has absolute control over all His servants. No one can resist His will or escape His authority. Every creature is subject to Him. This supremacy is not tyranny but the natural order—the Creator is above the creation. Understanding this helps the believer submit willingly, knowing that resistance to Allah is futile and acceptance brings peace.",
    "And He is the All-Wise, All-Aware": "Allah's dominance is coupled with perfect wisdom (Al-Hakeem) and complete awareness (Al-Khabeer). He does not exercise His power randomly or unjustly. Every decree, every test, every blessing comes from infinite wisdom and complete knowledge of what is best. When something difficult happens, the believer trusts that there is wisdom behind it, even if it is not immediately apparent. Allah knows the details of everything and makes decisions accordingly."
  },
  19: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Who is the best witness?\" Say, \"Allah is!\"": "The Prophet is commanded to establish that Allah is the greatest and most truthful witness. In any dispute or matter of truth, Allah's testimony is supreme. He sees everything, knows everything, and never errs. When the Prophet claims prophethood, Allah Himself is his witness—what greater validation could there be?",
    "He is a Witness between me and you": "Allah stands as a witness between the Prophet and those who dispute with him. He knows the Prophet is telling the truth, and He knows the disbelievers are lying. This will all be made clear on the Day of Judgment. This is both a validation of the Prophet's message and a warning to his opponents—their denial is recorded by the ultimate Witness.",
    "And this Quran has been revealed to me so that, with it, I may warn you and whoever it reaches": "The Quran was revealed to the Prophet Muhammad for the purpose of warning—warning his immediate audience and everyone the message reaches until the Day of Judgment. This verse establishes that the Quran's message is universal and timeless. Anyone who hears or reads the Quran is being warned and invited to guidance. The message is not limited to seventh-century Arabia.",
    "Do you ˹pagans˺ testify that there are other gods besides Allah?": "This is a challenge to the polytheists: Can you honestly testify that there are other gods worthy of worship alongside Allah? Do you have any real evidence for your claims?",
    "˹Then˺ say, \"I will never testify ˹to this˺!\"": "The Prophet declares his absolute refusal to ever acknowledge other gods. He will never give false testimony about the most important matter—the nature of divinity. His position is clear and uncompromising.",
    "˹And˺ say, \"There is only One God. And I totally reject whatever ˹idols˺ you associate with Him.\"": "The Prophet affirms absolute monotheism—there is only one God, Allah—and completely disassociates himself from all forms of polytheism. This declaration is the essence of Islam: La ilaha illa Allah (There is no god but Allah). The Prophet is not just passive about polytheism; he actively rejects and distances himself from it."
  },
  20: {
    "Those to whom We gave the Scripture recognize him ˹to be a true prophet˺ as they recognize their own children": "The Jews and Christians who had received previous scriptures knew the Prophet Muhammad as certainly as they knew their own sons. Their scriptures contained descriptions of the coming prophet—his characteristics, his location, his message—and Muhammad matched those descriptions perfectly. The companion Abdullah ibn Salam, a Jewish rabbi who accepted Islam, said: \"I knew him the moment I saw him, just as I know my own son, and my recognition of Muhammad is even stronger\" (Ibn Hibban). This verse exposes that the rejection of some People of the Book was not due to doubt but despite certainty.",
    "Those who have ruined themselves will never believe": "Despite this clear recognition, those who have destroyed their own souls through arrogance, jealousy, or worldly attachment refuse to believe. Their self-inflicted spiritual ruin prevents them from accepting what they know to be true. They have traded eternal success for temporary worldly interests—a losing transaction by any measure."
  },
  21: {
    "Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against Allah or deny His signs?": "This rhetorical question establishes that the greatest injustice is either inventing falsehoods about Allah—claiming He said things He did not say, attributing partners to Him, or misrepresenting His religion—or rejecting His clear signs and evidence. These are the most severe forms of wrongdoing because they relate to the most important matter: the truth about God.",
    "Indeed, the wrongdoers will never succeed": "Those who commit such injustice will never achieve true success. They may appear successful in this world temporarily, but ultimate and lasting success eludes them. Success in the sight of Allah requires truth, not lies; acceptance of signs, not rejection. The wrongdoers are on a path that leads only to failure."
  },
  22: {
    "˹Consider˺ the Day We will gather them all together": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will gather every single human being who ever lived—from the first person to the last. No one will be missing. This gathering is for accountability, and no one can avoid it. The enormity of that Day should occupy a believer's thoughts and motivate righteous action.",
    "then ask those who associated others ˹with Allah in worship˺, \"Where are those gods you used to claim?\"": "Allah will directly confront the polytheists with a devastating question: Where are the partners you worshipped? Where are the idols, the saints, the forces of nature, the ancestors, or whatever you elevated alongside Allah? Bring them forward to help you now. This question exposes the emptiness of polytheism. In this world, people may worship many things, but on that Day, the helplessness of all false gods will be laid bare."
  },
  23: {
    "Their only argument will be: \"By Allah, our Lord! We were never polytheists.\"": "When confronted with the reality of their situation, the polytheists will desperately lie, swearing by Allah that they never committed polytheism. This is remarkable—they will lie even on the Day when all lies are exposed. Their desperation drives them to deny what they spent their whole lives doing. But their own bodies will testify against them, as stated in other verses where hands, feet, and skin bear witness to what a person did (41:20-21)."
  },
  24: {
    "See how they will lie about themselves": "This is addressed to the Prophet and believers—observe how these people lie even about their own selves, denying what they clearly did. The lies they lived by in this world continue even into the afterlife, but now those lies are utterly useless.",
    "and how those ˹gods˺ they fabricated will fail them!": "All the false gods they invented and worshipped will completely abandon them. These supposed deities will be unable to help, intercede, or provide any support. Everything the polytheists built their lives around will vanish like a mirage. The idols they served will either be fuel for the fire along with them or will testify against them. The fabrications collapse, leaving the polytheists with nothing but regret."
  },
  25: {
    "There are some of them who ˹pretend to˺ listen to your recitation ˹of the Quran˺": "Among the disbelievers are those who come to hear the Prophet recite the Quran. They physically hear the sounds, but their listening is superficial—they are not genuinely seeking truth. They come perhaps out of curiosity, to find fault, or to mock, but not to learn or be guided.",
    "but We have cast veils over their hearts—leaving them unable to comprehend it—and deafness in their ears": "Because of their persistent rejection and insincerity, Allah has placed coverings over their hearts and heaviness in their ears. This is not arbitrary punishment but a consequence of their own choices. When someone repeatedly rejects truth, their capacity to receive it diminishes. It is like a person who keeps their eyes closed in bright sunlight—eventually, they lose the ability to handle light. This spiritual blindness and deafness is earned through stubbornness.",
    "Even if they were to see every sign, they still would not believe in them": "No matter how many miracles, proofs, or evidences are presented, they will not believe. Their rejection is not based on lack of evidence but on a fundamental unwillingness to accept. You could show them a thousand miracles, and they would explain each one away. This confirms that faith is ultimately a matter of the heart's disposition, not just intellectual proof.",
    "The disbelievers would ˹even˺ come to argue with you, saying, \"This ˹Quran˺ is nothing but ancient fables!\"": "Instead of reflecting on the Quran's message, they come to dispute and dismiss it as old stories—legends of previous peoples with no divine origin. This dismissal allows them to avoid engaging seriously with its message. Calling it \"fables\" is easier than addressing its profound truths. But the Quran challenged them: if it is just fables, produce something similar (2:23). They never could."
  },
  26: {
    "They turn others away from the Prophet and distance themselves as well": "These disbelievers do double harm: they not only reject the Prophet and his message themselves, but they also work to prevent others from accepting. They spread doubts, mockery, and lies to keep people away from guidance. And they personally maintain distance from the Prophet, ensuring they do not benefit from his teachings. This is active hostility, not passive disbelief.",
    "They ruin none but themselves, yet they fail to perceive it": "Despite all their efforts against Islam, they are ultimately only harming themselves. The Prophet's mission will succeed regardless of their opposition—Allah has guaranteed it. Their rejection does not diminish the truth; it only deprives them of its benefits. They think they are fighting the Prophet, but they are actually destroying their own souls. And the tragedy is they do not even realize it. They are blind to their own self-destruction, which makes their situation even more pitiable."
  },
  27: {
    "If only you could see when they will be detained before the Fire!": "This verse paints a vivid picture of the Day of Judgment when disbelievers will be brought face to face with the Hellfire. The phrase \"if only you could see\" is addressed to the Prophet and believers, inviting them to imagine this terrifying scene. These are the same people who denied, mocked, and turned away from the truth in this world. Now they stand before the very punishment they dismissed as fiction. The reality they refused to believe has become inescapable.",
    "They will cry, \"Oh! If only we could be sent back, we would never deny the signs of our Lord and we would ˹surely˺ be of the believers.\"": "In their utter desperation, they will wish for a second chance. They will express the deepest regret, promising that if they were returned to the world, they would believe and never reject Allah's signs again. This is the cry of every person who wasted their opportunity. But this world is the place of action, and the Hereafter is the place of consequences. The time for choices has passed. This should serve as a powerful reminder for the living: the time to believe and act righteously is now, not when facing punishment."
  },
  28: {
    "But no! ˹They only say this˺ because the truth they used to hide will become all too clear to them": "Allah exposes their insincerity. Their sudden desire to believe is not genuine repentance—it is merely a reaction to seeing the truth they had concealed from themselves. In this world, they buried the truth under layers of denial, arrogance, and distraction. Now that truth is fully exposed, and they cannot hide from it anymore. Their \"faith\" at this moment is not real faith but sheer panic.",
    "Even if they were to be sent back, they would certainly revert to what they were forbidden": "Allah, who knows all hearts, declares that even if these people were given another chance and sent back to the world, they would return to their old ways. They would fall back into disbelief, sin, and rejection just as before. This is because their problem was never lack of evidence—it was corruption of the heart. A second chance would not change who they fundamentally are.",
    "Indeed they are liars!": "Their promises to believe if given another chance are lies. They are lying even in that desperate moment. This confirms that their nature is deeply rooted in falsehood. They lied in this world about Allah, about the Prophet, and about the truth—and they continue lying even when standing before the Fire. This is the tragic consistency of a corrupted soul."
  },
  29: {
    "They insisted, \"There is nothing beyond this worldly life and we will never be resurrected.\"": "This verse captures the core belief of those who deny the Hereafter. They claim that this life is all there is—when you die, you cease to exist. There is no resurrection, no judgment, no accountability. This belief allows them to live however they want without fear of consequences. But this is a dangerous delusion. The Quran repeatedly emphasizes that resurrection is real and that every soul will be brought back to account for its deeds. Denying the Hereafter does not make it go away—it only leaves a person unprepared for it."
  },
  30: {
    "But if only you could see when they will be detained before their Lord!": "Again, we are invited to visualize the scene—these deniers of the Hereafter now standing before Allah Himself. The very Lord whose existence they questioned, whose resurrection they mocked, now holds them accountable. There is no escape, no denial possible anymore.",
    "He will ask ˹them˺, \"Is this ˹Hereafter˺ not the truth?\"": "Allah will question them directly: Is this not real? Is this not exactly what you were warned about? The question is rhetorical—of course it is true. But it forces them to confront their own denial and acknowledge their error.",
    "They will cry, \"Absolutely, by our Lord!\"": "Now they swear by Allah that yes, this is all true. The same people who denied the resurrection now confirm it under oath. But this admission comes too late. Belief on the Day of Judgment, when the reality is undeniable, does not count as faith. Faith must come in this world, when the unseen is still unseen.",
    "He will say, \"Then taste the punishment for your disbelief.\"": "Since they now admit the truth, the consequence follows logically: they must face the punishment they earned through their disbelief. The word \"taste\" implies a direct, personal experience of suffering. They will not merely observe punishment—they will feel it completely. This is the just outcome of rejecting truth when it was offered to them."
  },
  31: {
    "Losers indeed are those who deny the meeting with Allah": "The ultimate losers in existence are those who reject the reality that they will meet Allah. By denying this meeting, they waste their lives chasing temporary pleasures while ignoring eternal consequences. They lose the greatest opportunity any being can have: to prepare for and succeed in meeting their Creator.",
    "until the Hour takes them by surprise": "The Day of Judgment will come suddenly, without warning. Those who denied it will be caught completely off guard. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described the Hour's suddenness, saying it will come while two men are spreading a cloth to trade and they will not complete the transaction (Bukhari). There will be no time to prepare when it arrives.",
    "then they will cry, \"Woe to us for having ignored this!\"": "In that moment of shock, they will express intense regret for their neglect. \"Woe to us\" is a cry of utter despair. They will realize they had every opportunity to prepare but squandered it on distractions and denial. This regret is the most bitter kind—knowing that they were warned but chose to ignore.",
    "They will bear ˹the burden of˺ their sins on their backs": "Their sins will become like physical burdens they must carry. This is a powerful image: every lie, every act of cruelty, every moment of arrogance becomes a weight pressing down on them. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described that on the Day of Judgment, the disbeliever will come with sins like mountains (Muslim).",
    "Evil indeed is their burden!": "What a terrible load they carry! These burdens of sin will drag them down into punishment. Unlike worldly burdens that can be set down, these cannot be removed. This verse emphasizes the weight and horror of accumulated sins that were never repented for."
  },
  32: {
    "This worldly life is no more than play and amusement": "The Quran puts this world in perspective: compared to eternity, this life is like a child's game—temporary, unserious, and ultimately insignificant. People chase wealth, status, and pleasures as if they will last forever, but they are as fleeting as a game that ends when the bell rings. This does not mean life is meaningless, but rather that its true purpose is preparation for what comes after, not attachment to its temporary enjoyments.",
    "but far better is the ˹eternal˺ Home of the Hereafter for those mindful ˹of Allah˺": "The real prize, the true home, is the Hereafter—and it belongs to those who are conscious of Allah (the muttaqeen). Those who remember Allah, obey His commands, and avoid His prohibitions will find that the eternal home is incomparably better than anything this world offers. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that a space in Paradise equal to a whip is better than the entire world and everything in it (Bukhari).",
    "Will you not then understand?": "This is a call to use reason. When you compare temporary enjoyment with eternal bliss, when you weigh fleeting pleasures against everlasting rewards, the logical choice is obvious. Yet people continue to prioritize this world over the next. This question challenges the reader: Are you thinking clearly? Are you making rational decisions about your eternal future?"
  },
  33: {
    "We certainly know that what they say grieves you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah acknowledges the emotional pain the Prophet experiences from the harsh words, mockery, and rejection of his people. The Prophet cared deeply about guiding his people and was genuinely hurt when they called him a liar, a madman, or a sorcerer. Allah sees this pain and addresses it directly, showing His care for His Messenger's emotional wellbeing.",
    "It is not your honesty they question—it is Allah's signs that the wrongdoers deny": "This is a profound comfort. The Quraysh knew Muhammad was truthful—they had called him \"Al-Amin\" (the Trustworthy) his entire life. Their rejection was not about him personally; it was about rejecting the message itself. They denied Allah's signs out of arrogance, jealousy, and attachment to their ancestral ways. The Prophet should not take their rejection personally because it is not really about him—it is about their rebellion against Allah. Abu Jahl himself once admitted that he knew Muhammad was truthful but could not accept that prophethood went to the Banu Hashim clan instead of his own."
  },
  34: {
    "Indeed, messengers before you were rejected but patiently endured rejection and persecution": "The Prophet is reminded that he is not alone in facing rejection. Noah preached for 950 years and was mocked. Abraham was thrown into fire. Moses faced Pharaoh's tyranny. Jesus was rejected by his own people. Every messenger faced opposition, and every one of them responded with patience. This patience was not passive acceptance but active perseverance in the mission despite hardship.",
    "until Our help came to them": "The key point: Allah's help always came eventually. Noah was saved and his enemies drowned. Abraham emerged from the fire unharmed. Moses crossed the sea while Pharaoh's army perished. The help may not come immediately—it may take years or decades—but it always comes. This gives the Prophet and all believers hope: persist in righteousness, and Allah's support will arrive at the right time.",
    "And Allah's promise ˹to help˺ is never broken": "Allah's words and promises are absolute certainties. Unlike human promises that can be broken, Allah's word is unchangeable. If He promised to help His messengers and their followers, that help will come without fail. This is a source of unshakeable confidence for believers.",
    "And you have already received some of the narratives of these messengers": "The Prophet has been told the stories of previous messengers precisely so he can draw strength and lessons from them. These are not just historical tales but practical guidance showing that the path to victory goes through patience and perseverance."
  },
  35: {
    "If you find their denial unbearable, then build—if you can—a tunnel through the earth or stairs to the sky to bring them a ˹more compelling˺ sign": "Allah addresses the Prophet's intense desire to guide his people. The Prophet wished so strongly for their guidance that he might think: perhaps if I could bring them an even more spectacular miracle, they would believe. Allah says: even if you could dig into the earth or climb into the heavens to bring a different sign, it would not help. Their problem is not the type of miracle but their unwillingness to accept.",
    "Had Allah so willed, He could have guided them all": "If Allah had wanted, He could have created all humans to be believers with no free will. But He chose to give humanity choice, making faith meaningful. Forced belief is not true faith. The test of this life requires the freedom to choose or reject guidance.",
    "So do not be one of those ignorant ˹of this fact˺": "The Prophet is gently reminded not to exhaust himself over those who choose disbelief. Understanding that guidance is ultimately in Allah's hands—while the Prophet's duty is only to convey—brings peace. Ignoring this reality would be a form of ignorance. This is a lesson for all who call to Islam: do your best to convey the message, but do not destroy yourself over those who refuse to accept."
  },
  36: {
    "Only the attentive will respond ˹to your call˺": "Those who truly listen with open hearts and minds will accept the guidance. \"Attentive\" here means spiritually alive—people whose hearts are receptive and whose ears are open to truth. They are the ones who benefit from the Prophet's message. This is not about physical hearing but about inner receptivity.",
    "As for the dead, Allah will raise them up, then to Him they will ˹all˺ be returned": "The spiritually dead—those whose hearts are sealed due to their persistent rejection—are like corpses in terms of responding to guidance. They will not accept the message now. However, on the Day of Resurrection, Allah will raise even them from their graves, and they will return to Him for judgment. At that point, they will have no choice but to face the truth they rejected."
  },
  37: {
    "They ask, \"Why has no ˹other˺ sign been sent down to him from his Lord?\"": "The disbelievers repeatedly demanded specific miracles of their choosing, as if they could dictate to Allah what kind of proof should come. They ignored the greatest miracle already before them—the Quran itself—and kept asking for something else, perhaps hoping the Prophet would fail to produce it.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah certainly has the power to send down a sign\"": "Allah is fully capable of sending any miracle He wishes. There is no limitation on His power. He could split the moon, send angels visibly, or perform any wonder they demand.",
    "—though most of them do not know": "Despite Allah's unlimited power, most people do not understand the wisdom behind how and when miracles are sent. Miracles are not sent merely to satisfy curiosity or arrogance. They come according to Allah's wisdom, and when people reject miracles, they often face immediate punishment. Allah's restraint in sending certain signs is actually mercy, giving people more time to believe voluntarily."
  },
  38: {
    "All living beings roaming the earth and winged birds soaring in the sky are communities like yourselves": "This remarkable verse reveals that animals are not random creatures but organized communities with their own systems, behaviors, and purposes—just like human societies. Ants have colonies with division of labor. Bees have hives with queens and workers. Birds migrate in coordinated patterns. Each species has its own way of life ordained by Allah. This should inspire humility: humans are not the only significant creation. It also shows Allah's comprehensive care for all His creatures.",
    "We have left nothing out of the Record": "The \"Record\" (Al-Kitab) refers to the Preserved Tablet (Lawh al-Mahfuz) where everything is written, or it may refer to the Quran which contains all essential guidance. Nothing significant has been omitted. Every creature, every event, every matter of importance is accounted for. This is a statement of Allah's complete knowledge and perfect planning.",
    "Then to their Lord they will be gathered all together": "Even animals will be gathered on the Day of Judgment. They will be assembled so that justice can be served even among them—the hornless sheep will be given justice against the horned sheep that wronged it (Muslim). After this, they will be turned to dust. This gathering of all creatures demonstrates the comprehensive nature of Allah's justice and His control over all creation."
  },
  39: {
    "Those who deny Our signs are ˹wilfully˺ deaf and dumb—lost in darkness": "The disbelievers are described with three disabilities: deaf (they do not hear guidance), dumb (they do not speak truth or benefit others with good words), and lost in darkness (they cannot see the light of faith). These are spiritual conditions, not physical ones. Their senses work physically, but spiritually they are impaired because they have rejected the truth so persistently.",
    "Allah leaves whoever He wills to stray and guides whoever He wills to the Straight Way": "Ultimate guidance and misguidance are in Allah's hands. However, this is not arbitrary. Allah's \"will\" operates according to His wisdom and justice. He guides those who sincerely seek guidance and leaves astray those who insist on rejection. The Quran clarifies elsewhere that Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people (61:7) and that He guides those who turn to Him (13:27). So human choice plays a role in determining which category a person falls into."
  },
  40: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Imagine if you were overwhelmed by Allah's torment or the Hour—would you call upon any other than Allah ˹for help˺?": "This is a powerful argument against polytheism. When genuine disaster strikes—an earthquake, a storm at sea, a fatal illness, or the Day of Judgment itself—who do people instinctively call upon? The false gods they worshipped in times of ease are forgotten. Their hearts turn only to Allah because deep down, even the polytheist knows that only Allah can truly help.",
    "˹Answer me˺ if your claims are true!": "If your idols and false gods are real, if they have actual power, then call upon them in your moment of desperate need. The challenge exposes the falsehood of polytheism. No one genuinely relies on idols when their life is truly at stake."
  },
  41: {
    "No! He is the only One you would call": "Allah answers the question Himself: In moments of true crisis, you would call only upon Allah. This is the natural inclination (fitrah) within every human being—to turn to the Creator when all else fails. Even those who deny Allah in times of comfort find themselves pleading with Him in times of desperation.",
    "And if He willed, He could remove the affliction that made you invoke Him": "If Allah chooses, He can lift the hardship and rescue you. He is the only One with that power. The idols cannot remove even the smallest affliction.",
    "Only then will you forget whatever you associate with Him ˹in worship˺": "The sad irony: when Allah saves them, many people return to their old ways. They forget the moment when they knew only Allah could help. They go back to associating partners with Him. This cycle of crisis-remembrance followed by comfort-forgetfulness is a human weakness the Quran repeatedly highlights. The Prophet Yunus's people were an exception—when they finally believed, Allah removed the punishment (10:98)."
  },
  42: {
    "Indeed, We have sent messengers before you ˹O Prophet˺ to other people": "This is a continuation of the historical pattern. Allah sent messengers to many nations before the Prophet Muhammad, establishing that divine guidance has always been available to humanity.",
    "who We put through suffering and adversity ˹for their denial˺, so perhaps they would be humbled": "When those nations rejected their messengers, Allah tested them with hardships—poverty, famine, illness, and various difficulties. These were not punishments yet but warnings designed to shake them out of their heedlessness. The purpose was to make them turn back to Allah in humility. Adversity is often a mercy in disguise, a wake-up call before final destruction."
  },
  43: {
    "Why did they not humble themselves when We made them suffer?": "This is a rhetorical question expressing disappointment. When hardship came, they should have recognized it as a sign from Allah and turned to Him in repentance. That was the opportunity for salvation. But they missed it.",
    "Instead, their hearts were hardened": "Rather than softening through adversity, their hearts became even harder. Hardship that should have brought humility only increased their stubbornness. This is the dangerous state of a heart that has been corrupted by persistent sin—it loses its ability to respond to reminders.",
    "and Satan made their misdeeds appealing to them": "Satan played his role by beautifying their sins in their eyes. He made their disbelief seem reasonable, their rejection seem justified, and their lifestyle seem acceptable. This is how Satan works—he does not force anyone but makes wrong choices appear attractive. Under his influence, they saw no need to change."
  },
  44: {
    "When they became oblivious to warnings, We showered them with everything they desired": "This is a terrifying stage. When they completely ignored the reminders, Allah changed His approach: instead of hardship, He gave them abundance. Wealth, health, comfort, and pleasure poured upon them. This was not a reward but a trap—a final test before destruction. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: When you see Allah giving a servant whatever he wants despite his sins, know that it is gradual enticement (Ahmad).",
    "But just as they became prideful of what they were given, We seized them by surprise": "Right at the peak of their arrogance and enjoyment, when they thought they had everything figured out and felt most secure, destruction struck suddenly. There was no warning, no time to prepare or repent. The punishment came when they least expected it.",
    "then they instantly fell into despair!": "In one moment, they went from joy to utter hopelessness. All their wealth and pleasure vanished, replaced by destruction and despair. This is the fate of those who mistake Allah's patience for approval and His blessings for endorsement of their lifestyle."
  },
  45: {
    "So the wrongdoers were utterly uprooted": "Their destruction was complete—not a single one remained. Their civilization, their power, their legacy was erased. \"Utterly uprooted\" means they were cut off entirely, leaving no trace or continuation. This is the fate of nations that persist in wrongdoing after repeated warnings.",
    "And all praise is for Allah—Lord of all worlds": "The verse concludes with praise for Allah. This might seem surprising after describing destruction, but it emphasizes that Allah's justice is praiseworthy. The removal of oppressive, corrupt, and defiant peoples is a mercy to the earth and to future generations. When wrongdoers are uprooted, truth and justice prevail, and for that, Allah deserves praise."
  },
  46: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Imagine if Allah were to take away your hearing or sight, or seal your hearts—who else other than Allah could restore it?\"": "This verse presents a thought experiment: consider if Allah took away your ability to hear, see, or understand. These are fundamental faculties that humans depend on for everything. Could any idol, any human, any force restore them? The obvious answer is no. Only Allah, who granted these faculties in the first place, could restore them. This argument proves that only Allah deserves worship because only He has true power.",
    "See ˹O Prophet˺ how We vary the signs, yet they still turn away": "Allah presents arguments and signs in many different forms—logical, historical, natural, emotional—to reach people through various approaches. Despite this variety of evidence, people still turn away. This shows that their rejection is not due to insufficient evidence but to stubborn hearts. The problem is not with the message but with the recipients."
  },
  47: {
    "Ask, \"Imagine if Allah's punishment were to overwhelm you with or without warning—who would be destroyed other than the wrongdoers?\"": "Whether punishment comes suddenly (like an earthquake in the night) or openly (like an enemy army in daylight), only the wrongdoers will ultimately perish. This verse accomplishes two things: it warns the disbelievers that they are at risk, and it comforts the believers that Allah's punishment is precisely targeted. The righteous need not fear being destroyed alongside the wicked—Allah distinguishes between them."
  },
  48: {
    "We have sent messengers only as deliverers of good news and as warners": "This clarifies the role of all messengers throughout history. They are not sent to force people to believe or to control the unseen. Their job is twofold: to give good news of Paradise and Allah's mercy to those who believe, and to warn of Hellfire and Allah's punishment to those who reject. The choice remains with the people.",
    "Whoever believes and does good, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve": "For those who accept the message and follow it with righteous actions, the result is complete security. They will have no fear of what is to come (the Day of Judgment, punishment) and no grief over what has passed (worldly losses, missed opportunities). This is the ultimate peace that faith brings—freedom from fear and sadness. What greater reward could there be?"
  },
  49: {
    "But those who deny Our signs will be afflicted with punishment for their rebelliousness": "In contrast to the believers, those who reject Allah's signs will face punishment. The punishment is not arbitrary but directly caused by their \"rebelliousness\" (fisq)—their deliberate departure from obedience. They chose rebellion, and punishment is the natural consequence. The verse uses \"will be afflicted\" (touching them), indicating that the punishment will reach them personally and unavoidably."
  },
  50: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"I do not say to you that I possess Allah's treasuries": "The Prophet is commanded to clarify his human limitations. He does not claim to have access to Allah's infinite treasures of provision, mercy, or blessings to distribute as he wishes. He cannot give wealth, health, or success independently. He is a servant of Allah, not a controller of divine resources. This corrects any misconceptions that a prophet has godlike powers.",
    "or know the unseen": "The Prophet also does not claim knowledge of the unseen (al-ghayb)—future events, what is in people's hearts, or hidden realities. Only Allah has complete knowledge of the unseen. The Prophet knows only what Allah reveals to him. This distinguishes Islamic prophethood from fortune-telling or claims of omniscience.",
    "nor do I claim to be an angel": "The Prophet is human, not an angel. He eats, sleeps, experiences pain and joy, and will eventually die. Some people rejected him because he was \"just a man,\" but being human is part of the divine wisdom—a human messenger can be a practical example for other humans to follow.",
    "I only follow what is revealed to me": "The Prophet's role is to receive revelation and follow it, then convey it to others. He does not speak from his own desires regarding religion. His guidance comes entirely from Allah. This makes the message trustworthy—it is not human invention but divine communication.",
    "Say, \"Are those blind ˹to the truth˺ equal to those who can see?": "This rhetorical question highlights the obvious difference between one who accepts guidance (can see) and one who rejects it (is blind). They are clearly not equal in status, outcome, or understanding. The guided person navigates life successfully; the blind person stumbles into destruction.",
    "Will you not then reflect?\"": "The verse ends with an invitation to think. If the difference between guidance and blindness is so obvious, why would anyone choose blindness? Reflection should lead a reasonable person to accept the truth. The Quran consistently appeals to human intellect, asking people to think rather than blindly follow tradition or desire."
  },
  51: {
    "Warn with this ˹Quran˺ those who are awed by the prospect of being gathered before their Lord": "The Prophet is instructed to use the Quran as a tool of warning, specifically targeting those who have some fear and awareness of the Day of Judgment. These are people whose hearts are not completely sealed—they recognize that one day they will stand before Allah. The warning is most effective for those who already have this seed of awareness. People who completely deny the afterlife may not respond, but those with even a flicker of concern about meeting Allah can benefit from the reminder.",
    "—when they will have no protector or intercessor besides Him—": "On that Day, no one will be able to protect them from Allah's judgment except Allah Himself. No family member, no tribe, no wealth, no idol will be able to help. Intercession will only occur with Allah's permission, and even then, it will not help those who died upon disbelief. This reality should motivate people to seek Allah's pleasure now, while they have the chance.",
    "so perhaps they will be mindful ˹of Him˺": "The purpose of this warning is to develop taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to righteous action. The hope is that by hearing the Quran's message, people will become more aware of Allah, more careful about their deeds, and more devoted to obedience. The word \"perhaps\" indicates that the outcome depends on the individual's response."
  },
  52: {
    "˹O Prophet!˺ Do not dismiss those ˹poor believers˺ who invoke their Lord morning and evening, seeking His pleasure": "This verse was revealed when some wealthy Meccan leaders told the Prophet that they might consider listening to him if he would send away the poor and lowly believers like Bilal, Ammar, and Suhayb who gathered around him. The Prophet was instructed never to dismiss these sincere believers who worship Allah constantly—morning and evening—purely seeking His pleasure. Their poverty and low social status in society's eyes mean nothing compared to their spiritual worth. In Islam, a person's value is measured by their faith and deeds, not their wealth or lineage.",
    "You are not accountable for them whatsoever, nor are they accountable for you": "The Prophet is told that he bears no responsibility for their sins (if they had any), nor do they bear responsibility for his. Each person is accountable for themselves. This removes any excuse the elite might have for avoiding the Prophet's company because of who else was present.",
    "So do not dismiss them, or you will be one of the wrongdoers": "This is a strong warning to the Prophet—if he were to send away these sincere believers to please the arrogant elite, he would be committing injustice. This shows that in Islam, no worldly consideration can justify mistreating a believer. The Prophet never did dismiss them; this verse was a preemptive command ensuring he understood the gravity of such an action."
  },
  53: {
    "In this way We have tested some by means of others": "Allah explains His wisdom in allowing poor and wealthy, weak and powerful to coexist. The wealthy are tested by whether they will show arrogance toward the poor believers, and the poor are tested by whether they will remain patient and grateful despite their circumstances. The early acceptance of Islam by many poor people was itself a test for the proud elite.",
    "so those ˹disbelievers˺ may say, \"Has Allah favoured these ˹poor believers˺ out of all of us?\"": "The arrogant disbelievers mocked the idea that Allah would choose to guide slaves and poor people before the wealthy and powerful. They assumed that if the message were true, it would have come to them first due to their social status. This reveals their misunderstanding of divine criteria—Allah does not judge by wealth but by sincerity of heart.",
    "Does Allah not best recognize the grateful?": "Allah knows best who is truly grateful and deserving of guidance. The poor believers who accepted Islam were grateful for the truth regardless of the worldly cost, while the wealthy elite were ungrateful, rejecting guidance because of arrogance. Allah's choice of who receives guidance first reflects His perfect knowledge of hearts."
  },
  54: {
    "When the believers in Our revelations come to you, say, \"Peace be upon you!\"": "The Prophet is instructed to warmly welcome the believers with the greeting of peace. This honors them and shows them respect, regardless of their social status. It creates an atmosphere of love, acceptance, and brotherhood in the Muslim community.",
    "Your Lord has taken upon Himself to be Merciful": "Allah has obligated Himself to show mercy to His servants. This is not because anyone forced Him, but out of His own grace. This news is meant to comfort the believers and give them hope. No matter what they have done, Allah's door of mercy is always open.",
    "Whoever among you commits evil ignorantly ˹or recklessly˺ then repents afterwards and mends their ways": "This addresses those who sin out of ignorance, weakness, or momentary recklessness—not deliberate, defiant sin. The condition for forgiveness is genuine repentance followed by reformation of behavior. Repentance is not just saying \"sorry\" but actually changing one's ways.",
    "then Allah is truly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "For those who sincerely repent and improve, Allah guarantees forgiveness. He is Ghafoor (covers and forgives sins completely) and Raheem (shows continuous mercy). This gives tremendous hope to sinners who want to return to Allah."
  },
  55: {
    "This is how We make Our signs clear, so the way of the wicked may become distinct": "Allah explains His signs in detail so that the path of truth becomes clearly distinguishable from the path of falsehood. When guidance is clear, the deviation of criminals and evildoers also becomes obvious. This clarity removes any excuse—people cannot claim they did not know the difference between right and wrong."
  },
  56: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"I have been forbidden to worship those you invoke besides Allah.\"": "The Prophet is commanded to declare unequivocally that Allah has forbidden him from worshipping any of the idols, ancestors, or other beings that the polytheists worship. This is not a personal choice but a divine command. The prohibition is absolute—no compromise is possible on the issue of tawheed (monotheism).",
    "Say, \"I will not follow your desires": "The Prophet refuses to follow the whims and desires of the disbelievers. Their request for him to respect their gods or make compromises comes from desire, not from truth. Following people's desires instead of divine guidance is a recipe for disaster.",
    "for I then would certainly be astray and not one of those ˹rightly˺ guided.\"": "If the Prophet were to follow their desires even slightly, he would be misguided and lose his status among the rightly guided. This shows that guidance requires complete adherence to Allah's commands and complete rejection of polytheism—there is no middle ground."
  },
  57: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Indeed, I stand on a clear proof from my Lord—yet you have denied it\"": "The Prophet declares his position firmly: he has clear evidence from Allah—the Quran, the miracles, the logical arguments. He stands on solid ground. The disbelievers, despite all this evidence, have chosen to deny. The fault lies with them, not with the clarity of the message.",
    "That ˹torment˺ you seek to hasten is not within my power": "The disbelievers mockingly challenged the Prophet to bring the punishment he warned them about, asking why it had not come yet. The Prophet clarifies that he does not control the timing of Allah's punishment. He is a warner, not the one who executes judgment.",
    "It is only Allah Who decides ˹its time˺": "All decisions belong to Allah—when to punish, when to forgive, when to bring the Day of Judgment. The Prophet cannot accelerate or delay these matters. This is Allah's exclusive domain.",
    "He declares the truth. And He is the Best of Judges": "Allah speaks only truth and judges with perfect justice. His timing is always right, even when humans do not understand it. He is the best of all who distinguish between truth and falsehood, between the deserving and undeserving."
  },
  58: {
    "Say ˹also˺, \"If what you seek to hasten were within my power, the matter between us would have already been settled\"": "The Prophet states that if he had the power to bring punishment, he would have already settled the matter. The continuous mockery, persecution, and rejection he faced from the disbelievers would have been answered immediately. But this power belongs to Allah alone.",
    "But Allah knows the wrongdoers best": "Allah has complete knowledge of all wrongdoers—their deeds, their intentions, and the perfect time to hold them accountable. His delay is not inability but wisdom. He gives time for repentance, completes the evidence against them, and chooses the moment that demonstrates His perfect justice."
  },
  59: {
    "With Him are the keys of the unseen—no one knows them except Him": "Allah alone possesses the keys to all hidden knowledge. The Prophet (peace be upon him) explained that these include five things: knowledge of the Hour, knowledge of when rain will fall, knowledge of what is in the wombs, knowledge of what a person will earn tomorrow, and knowledge of where a person will die (Bukhari). No angel, prophet, or jinn has access to this knowledge except what Allah chooses to reveal.",
    "And He knows what is in the land and sea": "Allah's knowledge encompasses everything on earth and in the oceans—every creature, every event, every grain of sand, every drop of water. Nothing in the entire planet escapes His awareness. Scientists continue to discover new species and phenomena, but Allah has known them all from eternity.",
    "Not even a leaf falls without His knowledge": "This beautiful phrase illustrates the precision of Allah's knowledge. Every leaf that detaches from every tree on Earth—billions upon billions of events happening every moment—is known to Allah. This is not just passive knowledge; it happens by His will and decree.",
    "nor a grain in the darkness of the earth or anything—green or dry—but is ˹written˺ in a perfect Record": "Every seed buried in the soil, whether it sprouts or remains dormant, every living plant and every dead branch—all are recorded in the Preserved Tablet (Lawh al-Mahfuz). This comprehensive record demonstrates Allah's perfect knowledge and control over all creation. Nothing is random; everything is documented."
  },
  60: {
    "He is the One Who calls back your souls by night": "Sleep is described as a minor death—Allah takes the souls at night. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that sleep is the brother of death. Each night, we experience a temporary separation of soul and body, a daily reminder of our mortality and Allah's complete power over us.",
    "and knows what you do by day": "While we are awake and active during the day, Allah knows every action we perform—every deed, every word, every transaction. Nothing escapes His observation. Our daytime activities are all recorded.",
    "then revives you daily to complete your appointed term": "Each morning, Allah returns the soul to the body—this is why we wake up. This daily revival continues until we reach our appointed time of death. Every morning is a gift, a new opportunity given by Allah to live, worship, and improve.",
    "To Him is your ˹ultimate˺ return, then He will inform you of what you used to do": "Eventually, the cycle ends with permanent death, and everyone returns to Allah. At that point, He will inform each person of all their deeds—good and bad. This daily pattern of sleep and waking is a constant rehearsal for the greater death and resurrection."
  },
  61: {
    "He reigns supreme over all of His creation": "Allah is Al-Qahir—the Irresistible, the One who has complete dominance over all His servants. No one can resist His will or escape His authority. This supreme power means all creation is subject to Him.",
    "and sends recording-angels, watching over you": "Allah has appointed guardian angels (known as Kiraman Katibin—the Noble Recorders) who accompany each person and record all their deeds. One records good deeds, another records bad deeds. These angels never leave a person except in certain situations like using the restroom. Their constant presence means every deed is documented.",
    "When death comes to any of you, Our angels take their soul, never neglecting this duty": "When a person's appointed time arrives, the angels of death come to extract the soul. These angels never fail in their mission—they never come too early, too late, or miss anyone. They are perfectly obedient servants of Allah who execute their task without error."
  },
  62: {
    "Then they are ˹all˺ returned to Allah—their True Master": "After death, all souls return to Allah, who is their rightful Master (Mawla). He is the \"true\" Master because all other loyalties and protections in this world were temporary and illusory. In the end, everyone belongs to Allah alone.",
    "Judgment is His ˹alone˺": "All judgment and decision-making authority belongs exclusively to Allah. No one else can judge, pardon, or punish. Human courts have limited jurisdiction, but Allah's judgment is comprehensive and final.",
    "And He is the Swiftest Reckoner": "Allah will judge all of humanity with incredible speed. Despite the billions of souls and countless deeds, Allah will account for everything instantly. His knowledge is so complete that no time is needed for investigation or deliberation. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described that Allah will speak to each person individually, yet the entire judgment will be completed swiftly."
  },
  63: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Who rescues you from the darkest times on land and at sea?\"": "This question makes people reflect on their moments of greatest danger—when lost in a desert at night, when caught in a storm at sea, when facing any life-threatening situation. In those moments, who do they truly call upon? The \"darkest times\" refers to both literal darkness and metaphorical crises.",
    "He ˹alone˺ you call upon with humility, openly and secretly": "When disaster strikes, people pray to Allah with genuine humility—something they might not show in times of ease. They pray both openly (crying out) and secretly (in their hearts). The arrogance disappears, and sincere supplication emerges.",
    "\"If You rescue us from this, we will be ever grateful.\"": "In that desperate moment, people make promises to Allah: if You save me, I will be grateful, I will worship You properly, I will change my ways. These are the vows made in foxholes and on sinking ships—sincere in the moment, but often forgotten when safety returns."
  },
  64: {
    "Say, \"˹Only˺ Allah rescues you from this and any other distress": "The answer is clear: Allah alone saves people from danger—from that specific crisis and from every other difficulty they face. No idol, no human, no force of nature has this power. Only Allah can truly rescue.",
    "yet you associate others with Him ˹in worship˺\"": "Despite this obvious truth that they acknowledge in moments of crisis, people return to polytheism when the danger passes. They forget their promises and go back to worshipping or relying on other than Allah. This is the height of ingratitude and inconsistency—knowing who saves you but worshipping others."
  },
  65: {
    "Say, \"He ˹alone˺ has the power to unleash upon you a torment from above": "Allah can send punishment from above—storms, lightning, meteors, or any heavenly catastrophe. The people of Lot were destroyed by stones from the sky. This shows that the sky, which people might see as simply nature, is under Allah's command.",
    "or below you": "Punishment can also come from beneath—earthquakes, sinkholes, volcanic eruptions. The people of Qarun were swallowed by the earth. The ground people stand on is not secure without Allah's protection.",
    "or split you into ˹conflicting˺ factions and make you taste the violence of one another\"": "Perhaps the most relevant punishment is internal strife—Allah can divide a people into warring factions that fight and destroy each other. Civil wars, tribal conflicts, and sectarian violence are all manifestations of this. The Prophet (peace be upon him) sought refuge from this type of punishment, saying it is the most severe because it does not end (Muslim).",
    "See how We vary the signs, so perhaps they will comprehend": "Allah presents His signs and warnings in many different forms—some logical, some historical, some natural—hoping that through this variety, people will finally understand and take heed. Different approaches reach different hearts."
  },
  66: {
    "Still your people ˹O Prophet˺ have rejected this ˹Quran˺, although it is the truth": "Despite all the evidence, arguments, and clear signs, the Prophet's own people continue to reject the Quran. The tragedy is emphasized: it is \"the truth\"—not opinion, not speculation, but absolute truth—yet they deny it. Their rejection does not change its reality; it only harms themselves.",
    "Say, \"I am not a keeper over you\"": "The Prophet is reminded that his role is to convey, not to compel. He is not responsible for forcing people to believe or for controlling their choices. Each person will bear the consequences of their own decisions. This also provides comfort to the Prophet—the rejection is not his failure."
  },
  67: {
    "Every ˹destined˺ matter has a ˹set˺ time to transpire": "Everything that has been foretold—the punishment of disbelievers, the triumph of truth, the Day of Judgment—has an appointed time. Nothing happens before its time, and nothing is delayed beyond it. Allah's plan unfolds according to His perfect schedule.",
    "And you will soon come to know": "This is both a warning and a promise. The disbelievers will eventually see the reality of what they denied. Whether in this world through the victory of Islam and the defeat of its enemies, or in the Hereafter through judgment, they will come to know. The word \"soon\" emphasizes that from the perspective of eternity, this realization is imminent."
  },
  68: {
    "And when you come across those who ridicule Our revelations, do not sit with them unless they engage in a different topic": "Believers are commanded to avoid gatherings where Allah's signs are being mocked or disrespected. If people are making fun of the Quran, Islamic beliefs, or religious matters, a believer should not remain in that company. However, if the conversation changes to a neutral topic, it is permissible to stay. This protects the believer's heart from becoming desensitized to disrespect of sacred things.",
    "Should Satan make you forget, then once you remember, do not ˹continue to˺ sit with the wrongdoing people": "Allah acknowledges human weakness—sometimes a person may forget and remain in such company without realizing it. Satan can cause this forgetfulness. But as soon as one remembers, they must leave immediately. Continuing to sit after remembering would be deliberate participation in wrongdoing. This shows Allah's mercy in excusing genuine forgetfulness while holding people accountable once they become aware."
  },
  69: {
    "Those mindful ˹of Allah˺ will not be accountable for those ˹who ridicule it˺ whatsoever": "The God-conscious believers who avoid such gatherings will not bear any sin for the mockers' behavior. Each person is responsible for their own deeds. The believers have fulfilled their duty by leaving.",
    "—their duty is to advise, so perhaps the ridiculers will abstain": "However, believers should still try to advise and remind those who mock, hoping they might stop their behavior. The goal is not just personal safety but also trying to guide others. Perhaps through sincere advice, some of the mockers will develop taqwa and abandon their disrespect."
  },
  70: {
    "And leave those who take this faith ˹of Islam˺ as mere play and amusement": "Some people treat religion as entertainment—they engage with it casually, mock its rules, or practice it superficially without understanding its gravity. The Prophet is told to turn away from such people, not wasting energy on those who refuse to take truth seriously.",
    "and are deluded by ˹their˺ worldly life": "These people are deceived by the attractions of this world—its pleasures, its distractions, its temporary enjoyments. They prioritize worldly matters over eternal concerns, not realizing that this life is fleeting.",
    "Yet remind them by this ˹Quran˺, so no one should be ruined for their misdeeds": "Despite their attitudes, the Prophet should still remind them using the Quran. The purpose is to leave no excuse—they were warned. If they are ruined, it will be due to their own choices, not lack of guidance.",
    "They will have no protector or intercessor other than Allah": "On the Day of Judgment, these people will find no one to defend or help them except Allah. Their worldly supporters will abandon them, and their false gods will be useless.",
    "Even if they were to offer every ˹possible˺ ransom, none will be accepted from them": "They cannot buy their way out of punishment. No amount of wealth, no offering, no ransom will be accepted. Unlike worldly courts where money can sometimes influence outcomes, Allah's justice cannot be purchased.",
    "Those are the ones who will be ruined for their misdeeds": "Their destruction is a direct result of what they earned through their actions. They were not treated unjustly; they chose their path and received its consequences.",
    "They will have a boiling drink and painful punishment for their disbelief": "Their punishment in Hell includes drinking boiling water that tears apart their insides, along with other painful torments. This is the reward for their disbelief and mockery of the truth."
  },
  71: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Should we invoke, other than Allah, those ˹idols˺ which cannot benefit or harm us": "This rhetorical question highlights the absurdity of polytheism. Why would anyone worship things that have no power to help or hurt? These idols cannot answer prayers, cannot give or take, cannot do anything. Worshipping them is completely irrational.",
    "and turn back to disbelief after Allah has guided us?": "Even more absurd would be abandoning guidance after receiving it. To have found the truth and then return to falsehood is the worst kind of regression. It is like finding the exit from a burning building and then walking back into the flames.",
    "˹If we do so, we will be˺ like those disoriented by devils in the wilderness, while their companions call them to guidance, ˹saying˺, 'Come to us!'": "A powerful analogy is given: someone who leaves guidance is like a person in the desert who has been confused by demons. He wanders aimlessly while his friends, who are on the right path, call out to him to come back. But he is so disoriented that he cannot or will not respond. This describes the spiritual state of those who reject truth—they are lost while guidance calls to them.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah's guidance is the ˹only˺ true guidance": "The Prophet declares with certainty that only Allah's guidance is real guidance. All other paths—philosophical systems, man-made religions, personal whims—are ultimately false. There is one straight path, and it comes from Allah alone.",
    "And we are commanded to submit to the Lord of all worlds": "Muslims are commanded to submit completely to Allah, the Lord of everything that exists. This submission (Islam) is not oppressive but liberating—it frees a person from slavery to false gods, desires, and other humans."
  },
  72: {
    "establish prayer, and be mindful of Him": "Two essential commands follow from submission to Allah: establishing regular prayer (salah) and maintaining taqwa (consciousness of Allah in all matters). Prayer is the practical manifestation of submission—regular, disciplined worship that connects the servant to the Lord. Taqwa ensures that this consciousness extends beyond prayer times into all aspects of life.",
    "To Him you will all be gathered together": "The verse ends with a reminder of the inevitable gathering on the Day of Judgment. Everyone will return to Allah for accounting. This future reality should motivate present obedience."
  },
  73: {
    "He is the One Who created the heavens and the earth in truth": "Allah created the entire universe with purpose, wisdom, and truth—not randomly or in vain. Everything in creation has meaning, and creation itself testifies to the Creator. The universe operates on truth and will return to truth on the Day of Judgment.",
    "On the Day ˹of Judgment˺ He will say, 'Be!' And there will be!": "When Allah decides to bring about the Day of Judgment, He simply commands it, and it happens instantly. His word \"Be\" (Kun) is sufficient to accomplish anything. The resurrection that seems impossible to humans is effortless for Allah.",
    "His command is truth": "Whatever Allah decrees is true and will certainly occur. His words are not empty promises but absolute realities that manifest without fail.",
    "All authority is His ˹alone˺ on the Day the Trumpet will be blown": "On that Day when the Trumpet is blown to signal the resurrection, all authority and sovereignty belong exclusively to Allah. No king, president, or tyrant will have any power. All worldly hierarchies collapse, and only Allah's dominion remains.",
    "He is the Knower of all—seen or unseen": "Allah knows everything that is visible and hidden—the physical world we can observe and the spiritual realms we cannot see. Nothing is beyond His knowledge.",
    "And He is the All-Wise, All-Aware": "Allah combines perfect wisdom (knowing why and how to do things) with complete awareness (knowing all details and circumstances). This combination ensures that all His decisions are perfectly correct."
  },
  74: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Abraham said to his father, Ȃzar, \"Do you take idols as gods?\"": "The Quran now presents the story of Prophet Abraham (Ibrahim, peace be upon him) as an example of someone who recognized truth and rejected falsehood despite his environment. Abraham questioned his own father, Azar, about idol worship. This was not disrespectful but a sincere challenge to make his father think. Asking questions is often the first step toward guidance.",
    "It is clear to me that you and your people are entirely misguided.\"": "Abraham declared plainly that his father and his people were in obvious error. He did not sugarcoat the truth to please his family or avoid conflict. This shows the courage required to speak truth even to those closest to us. Family ties do not justify remaining silent about falsehood. Abraham's directness came from love—he wanted to save his father from destruction."
  },
  75: {
    "We also showed Abraham the wonders of the heavens and the earth, so he would be sure in faith": "Allah granted Abraham special insight into the dominion of the heavens and earth. He was shown the signs of Allah's power in creation—the vastness of the universe, the precision of natural laws, the beauty and complexity of existence. This was not just physical observation but spiritual vision that led to absolute certainty (yaqeen) in faith. Allah prepares those He chooses for prophethood by showing them His signs in profound ways."
  },
  76: {
    "When the night grew dark upon him, he saw a star and said, \"This is my Lord!\"": "This begins Abraham's famous demonstration of logical reasoning about God. Some scholars say Abraham was genuinely searching for truth in his youth, while others say he was using this as an argument against his people who worshipped celestial bodies. Either way, he pointed to a star—bright and prominent in the night sky—and considered it as a potential lord.",
    "But when it set, he said, \"I do not love things that set.\"": "When the star disappeared below the horizon, Abraham rejected it as a god. His reasoning was simple but profound: something that disappears, something temporary, something that has no control over its own presence—cannot be the Lord of all. A true God must be eternal and unchanging. This began his process of elimination."
  },
  77: {
    "Then when he saw the moon rising, he said, \"This one is my Lord!\"": "The moon, larger and brighter than any star, rose in the sky. Abraham considered it next—perhaps this greater celestial body was the lord. His people worshipped the moon, so this was directly relevant to their beliefs.",
    "But when it disappeared, he said, \"If my Lord does not guide me, I will certainly be one of the misguided people.\"": "When the moon also set, Abraham again rejected it. But this time, he added a crucial acknowledgment: he recognized that finding the true God requires divine guidance. Human intellect alone, without Allah's help, cannot reach complete truth. This humble statement shows that Abraham understood his need for Allah's guidance and did not rely solely on his own reasoning."
  },
  78: {
    "Then when he saw the sun shining, he said, \"This must be my Lord—it is the greatest!\"": "Finally, the sun rose—the most powerful and brilliant object visible to humans, the source of light and heat that sustains life on earth. Abraham considered it: surely something this magnificent and powerful must be the lord. \"It is the greatest\" reflects the common human tendency to equate size and power with divinity.",
    "But again when it set, he declared, \"O my people! I totally reject whatever you associate ˹with Allah in worship˺.\"": "But the sun too set. Despite its magnificence, it was also subject to the cycle of rising and setting—not in control of its own movement. At this point, Abraham made his final declaration: he completely dissociated himself from all forms of polytheism. Stars, moon, sun—none of them qualified as God. They were all created things, controlled by something greater. His rejection was total and uncompromising."
  },
  79: {
    "I have turned my face towards the One Who has originated the heavens and the earth": "Abraham declared his commitment to the true God—not any visible object, but the One who created all visible objects. The Creator of the heavens and earth is not part of creation but above and beyond it. Abraham turned his entire being (\"face\" represents complete attention and devotion) toward this unseen Creator.",
    "—being upright—": "The word \"hanif\" means one who turns away from falsehood toward truth, inclining naturally toward monotheism. Abraham was upright in his faith, not twisted by the polytheism of his environment. This term became associated with the pure monotheistic tradition that predated and led to Islam.",
    "and I am not one of the polytheists": "Abraham's final declaration: he completely separated himself from polytheism. He would not worship anything alongside Allah—not stars, not moon, not sun, not idols, not ancestors. This was his clear, public stance against everything his society believed. This story shows that through sincere reflection on creation, combined with Allah's guidance, a person can arrive at pure monotheism even in a polytheistic environment."
  },
  80: {
    "And his people argued with him": "After Abraham declared his rejection of polytheism and his commitment to the One True God, his people did not simply accept his message. Instead, they debated and argued with him, trying to defend their idolatry and make him fear their gods. This is a common response when truth challenges established falsehood—people argue rather than reflect.",
    "He responded, \"Are you arguing with me about Allah, while He has guided me?\"": "Abraham expressed amazement that they would argue about Allah when Allah had clearly guided him to the truth. The one who has received guidance has certainty, while those still in darkness have only speculation. Abraham's confidence came from divine guidance, not personal opinion.",
    "I am not afraid of whatever ˹idols˺ you associate with Him—˹none can harm me,˺ unless my Lord so wills": "Abraham declared his complete lack of fear toward their false gods. He knew these idols had no power whatsoever—they could not harm him in any way. However, he acknowledged that if any harm came to him, it would only be by Allah's will, not by any power of the idols. This shows perfect tawheed: recognizing that all power belongs to Allah alone.",
    "My Lord encompasses everything in ˹His˺ knowledge": "Allah's knowledge is comprehensive—nothing escapes it. He knows the plots of Abraham's enemies, the weakness of their idols, and the outcome of every situation. This knowledge means Allah is in complete control, and Abraham trusted in that control.",
    "Will you not be mindful?": "Abraham invited his people to reflect and remember. The evidence was clear if only they would use their minds. This question was not meant to insult but to awaken them from heedlessness."
  },
  81: {
    "And how should I fear your associate-gods, while you have no fear in associating ˹others˺ with Allah—a practice He has never authorized?": "Abraham presented a powerful counter-argument. His people wanted him to fear their powerless idols, yet they themselves had no fear of committing the greatest sin: associating partners with Allah, the All-Powerful Creator. They feared statues that could do nothing while not fearing the One who controls everything. This is completely backwards. Furthermore, their polytheism had no divine authorization—no proof, no scripture, no logical basis.",
    "Which side has more right to security? ˹Tell me˺ if you really know!\"": "Abraham posed the ultimate question: who should really feel safe? The one who worships the All-Powerful Creator alone, or those who worship powerless idols while offending the true God? The answer is obvious to anyone who thinks clearly. True security comes from being on Allah's side, not from appeasing false gods."
  },
  82: {
    "It is ˹only˺ those who are faithful and do not tarnish their faith with falsehood who are guaranteed security and are ˹rightly˺ guided": "This verse provides the definitive answer to Abraham's question. True security belongs to those who believe in Allah and do not mix their faith with \"dhulm\" (wrongdoing/injustice). When this verse was revealed, the companions were worried, thinking \"dhulm\" meant any sin. But the Prophet (peace be upon him) explained that here it refers specifically to shirk (polytheism), citing the verse: \"Indeed, shirk is a great injustice\" (31:13). So the one who believes in Allah alone, without associating any partners, has true security in this life and the next, and is rightly guided to the straight path."
  },
  83: {
    "This was the argument We gave Abraham against his people": "Allah clarifies that the powerful reasoning Abraham used came from Allah Himself. His ability to argue convincingly against polytheism was a divine gift. The logical proofs, the fearless courage, the clear thinking—all were from Allah's guidance. This teaches us that effective dawah (calling to Islam) requires divine assistance, not just human cleverness.",
    "We elevate in rank whoever We please": "Allah raises people in status according to His will. Abraham was elevated to the rank of prophet and close friend of Allah (Khalilullah) because of his faith, obedience, and dedication to truth. This elevation is not random but based on Allah's perfect wisdom.",
    "Surely your Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing": "Allah's decisions about whom to guide, whom to elevate, and whom to give prophethood are based on His complete wisdom and perfect knowledge. He knows who deserves these blessings and who will use them properly."
  },
  84: {
    "And We blessed him with Isaac and Jacob": "As a reward for Abraham's steadfast faith and sacrifice, Allah blessed him with righteous descendants. Isaac (Ishaq) was born to him through Sarah in his old age, and Jacob (Ya'qub) was Isaac's son. Both became prophets, continuing Abraham's mission of monotheism.",
    "We guided them all as We previously guided Noah": "Allah emphasizes that guidance is His gift. He guided Isaac and Jacob just as He had guided Noah (Nuh) before Abraham. Noah was among the earliest prophets, and his story of patient preaching for 950 years serves as an example for all messengers.",
    "and those among his descendants: David, Solomon, Job, Joseph, Moses, and Aaron": "From the lineage of these prophets came more prophets: David (Dawud), the king-prophet who received the Psalms; Solomon (Sulayman), who was given unprecedented kingdom and wisdom; Job (Ayyub), the example of patience in suffering; Joseph (Yusuf), who rose from slavery to leadership in Egypt; Moses (Musa), who freed the Israelites and received the Torah; and Aaron (Harun), Moses's brother and helper. Each had a unique mission, but all called to the worship of Allah alone.",
    "This is how We reward the good-doers": "Prophethood and righteous descendants are among Allah's greatest rewards for those who do good. Abraham's excellence (ihsan) in worship and obedience was rewarded with a legacy of prophets that would continue until the Day of Judgment. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) himself is from Abraham's lineage through Ishmael."
  },
  85: {
    "Likewise, ˹We guided˺ Zachariah, John, Jesus, and Elias, who were all of the righteous": "The list of guided prophets continues: Zachariah (Zakariyya), the priest who cared for Mary and was blessed with John in his old age; John (Yahya), who called people to repentance and verified Jesus; Jesus (Isa), who performed miracles by Allah's permission and called to pure monotheism; and Elias (Ilyas), who confronted idol-worship in his time. All of them were righteous—they practiced what they preached and lived lives of devotion to Allah."
  },
  86: {
    "˹We also guided˺ Ishmael, Elisha, Jonah, and Lot, favouring each over other people ˹of their time˺": "More prophets are mentioned: Ishmael (Isma'il), Abraham's first son through Hagar, who helped build the Kaaba and from whose lineage Prophet Muhammad came; Elisha (Al-Yasa'), who succeeded Elias as prophet; Jonah (Yunus), who was swallowed by the whale and whose people uniquely repented and were saved; and Lot (Lut), Abraham's nephew who preached against homosexuality and immorality in Sodom. Each was chosen and favored above the people of their era—a special status granted by Allah."
  },
  87: {
    "And ˹We favoured˺ some of their forefathers, their descendants, and their brothers": "The blessing extended through entire family networks—fathers, children, and siblings were included in this chain of guidance. Righteousness often runs in families, not because of genetics but because of the environment of faith, teaching, and example that righteous parents provide.",
    "We chose them and guided them to the Straight Path": "Allah emphasizes two aspects: He chose them (ijtaba—a deliberate selection) and He guided them. Being chosen for prophethood was not random but based on Allah's knowledge of their worthiness. And the guidance to the Straight Path is the same guidance all prophets called to: pure monotheism and obedience to Allah."
  },
  88: {
    "This is Allah's guidance with which He guides whoever He wills of His servants": "The guidance given to all these prophets is Allah's guidance—one consistent message of monotheism throughout history. Allah grants this guidance to whomever He wills among His servants, based on His perfect knowledge of who is sincere and deserving.",
    "Had they associated others with Him ˹in worship˺, their ˹good˺ deeds would have been wasted": "This is a powerful warning: even these great prophets—had they committed shirk (which they never did)—would have had all their deeds nullified. Shirk destroys all good deeds because it negates the very foundation of acceptable worship: sincerity to Allah alone. This shows that no one is exempt from this rule, and it emphasizes the absolute importance of tawheed (monotheism)."
  },
  89: {
    "Those were the ones to whom We gave the Scripture, wisdom, and prophethood": "Allah blessed these prophets with three things: Scripture (divine revelation in written form), wisdom (understanding and ability to apply that knowledge), and prophethood (the mission of conveying Allah's message). These are the greatest gifts Allah can bestow on a human being.",
    "But if these ˹pagans˺ disbelieve in this ˹message˺, then We have already entrusted it to a people who will never disbelieve in it": "If the Quraysh and other disbelievers reject the message, it does not matter—Allah has already guaranteed that there will always be people who believe in and preserve His message. Some scholars say this refers to the companions and the Muslim ummah. Others say it refers to the sincere believers throughout history. The message will never be without its true followers."
  },
  90: {
    "These ˹prophets˺ were ˹rightly˺ guided by Allah, so follow their guidance": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is commanded to follow the guidance of the previous prophets. This does not mean following their specific laws (sharia), which were for their times, but following their fundamental message of tawheed, their patience in adversity, their trust in Allah, and their methods of calling to truth. The core of all prophetic guidance is the same.",
    "Say, \"I ask no reward of you for this ˹Quran˺—it is a reminder to the whole world\"": "The Prophet declares that he seeks no payment, no wealth, no worldly benefit for conveying the message. This removes any suspicion that he might have selfish motives. The Quran is a reminder (dhikra) not just for Arabs or for that era, but for all of humanity until the Day of Judgment. Its guidance is universal and timeless."
  },
  91: {
    "And they have not shown Allah His proper reverence when they said, \"Allah has revealed nothing to any human being.\"": "Some people—whether certain Jews, pagans, or others—claimed that Allah never sent revelation to any human. This statement shows a profound disrespect and misunderstanding of Allah. It implies He created humanity and then abandoned them without guidance. But Allah, in His mercy and wisdom, would never leave creation without direction.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Who then revealed the Book brought forth by Moses as a light and guidance for people": "The Prophet is told to challenge this claim with obvious evidence: What about the Torah that Moses brought? It was clearly a light (illuminating truth) and guidance for people. Even those making this claim acknowledged Moses. So their statement contradicts known history.",
    "which you split into separate sheets—revealing some and hiding much?": "This addresses the corruption of previous scriptures. Some people took the Torah and divided it, making public only the parts they liked while concealing portions that contradicted their interests—including prophecies about the final prophet. This selective approach to scripture is a form of dishonesty.",
    "You have been taught ˹through this Quran˺ what neither you nor your forefathers knew.\"": "The Quran has brought knowledge that neither the current generation nor their ancestors possessed. This includes detailed accounts of prophets, clarifications of corrupted teachings, and guidance for all aspects of life. The Quran's knowledge proves its divine origin.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah ˹revealed it˺!\" Then leave them to amuse themselves with falsehood": "The answer is simple and certain: Allah revealed all true scripture. After stating this truth, the Prophet is told not to exhaust himself arguing with those who persist in falsehood. Let them play with their false ideas—they will face the consequences."
  },
  92: {
    "This is a blessed Book which We have revealed": "The Quran is described as \"blessed\" (mubarak)—it brings goodness wherever it goes. Reciting it is rewarded, following it brings success, and it serves as a source of healing, guidance, and mercy. No other book in existence carries such blessing.",
    "—confirming what came before it—": "The Quran confirms the original messages of previous scriptures—the Torah, Psalms, Gospel, and others. It does not contradict their authentic teachings but validates them while also correcting corruptions that entered over time. This continuity shows the unity of Allah's message throughout history.",
    "so you may warn the Mother of Cities and everyone around it": "The \"Mother of Cities\" is Makkah—called this because it is the site of the first house of worship (the Kaaba), the center of the earth according to Islamic tradition, and the birthplace of Islam. The Prophet's warning began there but extends to everyone around it—meaning the entire world. Makkah was the starting point, not the limit.",
    "Those who believe in the Hereafter ˹truly˺ believe in it and guard their prayers": "Those who genuinely believe in the afterlife will naturally believe in the Quran because it speaks extensively about that reality. And true belief manifests in action—specifically, they guard their prayers. Prayer is the practical test of faith; those who truly believe will not neglect their connection with Allah."
  },
  93: {
    "Who does more wrong than the one who fabricates lies against Allah": "The worst type of wrongdoer is someone who invents falsehoods and attributes them to Allah. This includes those who claim Allah said things He never said, who invent religious rulings without authority, or who distort His message.",
    "or claims, \"I have received revelations!\"—although nothing was revealed to them": "Equally wrong is the false prophet—someone who claims to receive revelation from Allah when they have received nothing. This is among the most serious deceptions because it misleads people about their eternal fate. Musaylimah the Liar was such a person, and he faced a terrible end.",
    "or the one who says, \"I can reveal the like of Allah's revelations!\"?": "Also among the greatest wrongdoers is someone who arrogantly claims they can produce something like the Quran. This was the challenge the Quran issued (2:23), and no one has ever succeeded. Those who claim they can match it show the height of arrogance.",
    "If you ˹O Prophet˺ could only see the wrongdoers in the throes of death while the angels are stretching out their hands ˹saying˺, \"Give up your souls!\"": "The scene shifts to the moment of death for these wrongdoers. The angels of death come to extract their souls, but these souls do not want to leave—they resist because they know what awaits them. The angels stretch out their hands, demanding the souls come out.",
    "\"Today you will be rewarded with the torment of disgrace for telling lies about Allah and for being arrogant towards His revelations!\"": "At that terrible moment, the angels announce their punishment: disgraceful torment. The reasons are stated clearly—lying about Allah and showing arrogance toward His revelations. These two sins—fabrication and pride—led to their destruction."
  },
  94: {
    "˹Today˺ you have come back to Us all alone as We created you the first time": "On the Day of Judgment, every person stands before Allah alone—no companions, no supporters, no crowd to hide behind. Just as we were born alone, we face judgment alone. All the groups, tribes, and alliances of this world mean nothing.",
    "—leaving behind everything We have provided you with": "All worldly possessions are left behind—wealth, houses, cars, status, everything. None of it accompanies you to the grave or beyond. What you spent a lifetime accumulating is now irrelevant. Only deeds matter.",
    "We do not see your intercessors with you—those you claimed were Allah's partners ˹in worship˺": "Allah points out the absence of their supposed intercessors—the idols, saints, or other beings they worshipped hoping for their help on this Day. Where are they now? They cannot be found. They have abandoned their worshippers completely.",
    "All your ties have been broken and all your claims have let you down": "Every connection they relied upon has been severed. Every claim they made about their gods has proven false. They stand exposed, helpless, and alone—realizing too late that only Allah could have helped them, but they rejected Him."
  },
  95: {
    "Indeed, Allah is the One Who causes seeds and fruit stones to sprout": "Allah splits open seeds and date stones, causing new life to emerge from what appears dead and dry. A tiny seed contains within it the blueprint for an entire tree. This is Allah's creative power at work in the simplest, most everyday miracles that people often overlook.",
    "He brings forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living": "Allah creates living things from non-living matter—a chick from an egg, a plant from a seed, a human from earth. And He brings the dead from the living—an egg from a chicken, a seed from a plant. This cycle demonstrates His absolute control over life and death.",
    "That is Allah! How can you then be deluded ˹from the truth˺?": "After presenting this evidence of Allah's power in everyday nature, the question is posed: with all these signs around you, how can you be deceived into worshipping anything else? The delusion of polytheism becomes even more absurd in light of these obvious truths."
  },
  96: {
    "He causes the dawn to break": "Every morning, Allah splits the darkness of night to bring forth the light of dawn. This daily miracle, so common that we take it for granted, is a sign of Allah's continuous creative activity. He could keep the world in perpetual darkness, but He chooses to give us light.",
    "and has made the night for rest": "The night is designed for rest and tranquility. The darkness signals our bodies to slow down, the temperature drops, and the world becomes quiet. This is Allah's mercy—giving us regular intervals of recovery from the demands of the day.",
    "and ˹made˺ the sun and the moon ˹to travel˺ with precision": "The sun and moon move according to exact calculations. Their positions can be predicted centuries in advance because they follow precise patterns set by Allah. This precision enables us to calculate time, seasons, and navigate—all practical benefits from their perfect design.",
    "That is the design of the Almighty, All-Knowing": "All this precision comes from the Al-Aziz (the Almighty, who has power to implement His design) and Al-Aleem (the All-Knowing, who has the knowledge to create such perfect systems). Power without knowledge creates chaos; knowledge without power is ineffective. Allah has both perfectly."
  },
  97: {
    "And He is the One Who has made the stars as your guide through the darkness of land and sea": "Before modern technology, travelers on land and sailors at sea navigated by the stars. The North Star and constellations served as reliable guides through the dark desert or open ocean. Allah created these celestial signposts for human benefit. Even today, stars serve as backup navigation systems.",
    "We have already made the signs clear for people who know": "The signs are evident to those who have knowledge and reflect. Knowledge here means understanding—connecting what you see to the Creator behind it. Those who truly know recognize Allah's hand in every natural phenomenon."
  },
  98: {
    "And He is the One Who originated you all from a single soul": "All of humanity descended from one person—Adam (peace be upon him). This shared origin should create unity and humility. No race or family can claim inherent superiority because everyone traces back to the same source.",
    "then assigned you a place to live and another to ˹be laid to˺ rest": "Each person has a temporary dwelling in this world and a final resting place (the grave or, more broadly, the afterlife). Some scholars interpret this as the womb (temporary dwelling) and the earth (resting place). Either way, it emphasizes the temporary nature of our earthly existence.",
    "We have already made the signs clear for people who comprehend": "Understanding these signs requires comprehension (fiqh)—deep understanding that goes beyond surface knowledge. Those who truly comprehend see Allah's wisdom in human origin and destiny."
  },
  99: {
    "And He is the One Who sends down rain from the sky—causing all kinds of plants to grow": "Water descends from above, and through it Allah brings forth incredible diversity of plant life. The same water produces different plants depending on the soil, climate, and seeds. This transformation of rain into vegetation is a sign of Allah's creative power.",
    "—producing green stalks from which We bring forth clustered grain": "From the green shoots come grains stacked upon each other—wheat, barley, rice, corn. These staple foods that sustain humanity grow in this orderly, clustered pattern designed for easy harvest and consumption.",
    "And from palm trees come clusters of dates hanging within reach": "Date palms produce bunches of dates that hang accessibly. This accessible design makes harvesting easier—another sign of Allah's care for human needs. Dates are highly nutritious and were a staple food in Arabia.",
    "˹There are˺ also gardens of grapevines, olives, and pomegranates, similar ˹in shape˺ but dissimilar ˹in taste˺": "Different fruits grow from the same water and often similar conditions, yet each has its unique taste, texture, and properties. Grapes, olives, and pomegranates may have similar-looking leaves or trees, but their fruits are completely different. This diversity from unity points to a deliberate, creative Designer.",
    "Look at their fruit as it yields and ripens!": "Allah invites contemplation: observe how fruit develops from blossom to green fruit to ripe produce. This gradual process, happening continuously all around us, is a sign for those who pay attention. The transformation is miraculous if we stop to consider it.",
    "Indeed, in these are signs for people who believe": "These natural phenomena are signs (ayat) pointing to Allah—but only for those who believe. Belief opens the heart to see divine wisdom in creation. Without belief, a person might see only random processes, missing the deeper meaning."
  },
  100: {
    "Yet they associate the jinn with Allah ˹in worship˺, even though He created them": "Some people worshipped the jinn, believing them to have divine powers or special influence with Allah. But the jinn themselves are created beings—Allah made them from smokeless fire. How can something created be a partner with the Creator? This is utterly illogical.",
    "and they falsely attribute to Him sons and daughters out of ignorance": "Various groups claimed Allah had children—some Arabs said the angels were Allah's daughters, some Christians said Jesus was Allah's son, some claimed the jinn were Allah's offspring. All of this was invented without any knowledge or evidence—pure fabrication based on ignorance.",
    "Glorified and Exalted is He above what they claim!": "Allah is far above and beyond such false descriptions. He is glorified (Subhanahu)—free from all imperfections—and exalted (Ta'ala)—high above all their invented claims. These words express Allah's absolute transcendence above human misconceptions."
  },
  101: {
    "˹He is˺ the Originator of the heavens and earth": "Allah is Badi'—the One who originates, creates without any prior model or blueprint. The heavens and earth came into existence by His will alone, not through any natural process or pre-existing material. This creative power is uniquely His.",
    "How could He have children when He has no mate?": "The logical argument is presented: children, in any normal understanding, require two parents. Allah has no spouse, no partner, no equal—so how could He have children? The very concept is incompatible with His nature. He is utterly unique, beyond the categories that apply to His creation.",
    "He created all things and has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of everything": "Allah created everything that exists—including those beings falsely called His children. The Creator cannot be in the category of His creation. And His knowledge is complete—He knows everything about everything He created, and He certainly knows that these claims about Him are false."
  },
  102: {
    "That is Allah—your Lord!": "After presenting all these proofs and arguments, the conclusion is declared: this is Allah—the One you should recognize as your Lord. Not the idols, not the jinn, not the celestial bodies, not any created thing—but Allah alone.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "The fundamental declaration of Islamic faith: La ilaha illa Huwa. No deity deserves worship except Allah. This is not just a theological statement but a complete worldview that shapes how a Muslim lives, thinks, and prioritizes.",
    "˹He is˺ the Creator of all things, so worship Him ˹alone˺": "Because Allah created everything, He alone deserves worship. This is the logical consequence of His creative sovereignty. The Creator has rights over creation; the created has no right to be worshipped alongside the Creator.",
    "And He is the Maintainer of everything": "Allah is the Wakeel—the Trustee, Guardian, and Maintainer of all things. He not only created everything but continues to sustain and manage it. He is the one to rely upon for all affairs. This combines His power with His ongoing involvement in creation."
  },
  103: {
    "No vision can encompass Him, but He encompasses all vision": "Human eyes cannot fully perceive or comprehend Allah—He is beyond the capacity of created vision to encompass. However, Allah sees everything—all vision is within His perception. He sees us completely while we cannot see Him in this life. This asymmetry reflects His transcendence above creation.",
    "For He is the Most Subtle, All-Aware": "Allah is Al-Latif—the Most Subtle, the One whose knowledge and action penetrate to the finest details in ways we cannot perceive. He is also Al-Khabir—the All-Aware, who knows every detail of everything. These names explain why we cannot encompass Him—He is too subtle and too vast for human perception, yet He is fully aware of us down to our innermost thoughts."
  },
  104: {
    "Indeed, there have come to you insights from your Lord": "The Quran and the Prophet's message provide clear insights (basaa'ir)—spiritual vision that illuminates truth from falsehood. These are not mere opinions or human philosophies but divine insights from the Lord of all creation. They enable people to see reality clearly—the existence of Allah, the truth of the Hereafter, and the path to salvation.",
    "So whoever chooses to see, it is for their own good": "Whoever opens their eyes and heart to these insights will benefit themselves. Guidance is not a favor to Allah or to the Prophet—it is a favor to oneself. When you accept truth and live by it, you are the one who gains success in this life and the next.",
    "But whoever chooses to be blind, it is to their own loss": "Conversely, whoever refuses to see—who closes their eyes to the clear evidence—harms only themselves. Their blindness does not diminish Allah's sovereignty or the Prophet's mission. It only leads to their own destruction. The loss is entirely theirs.",
    "And I am not a keeper over you": "The Prophet clarifies his role once again: he is not a guardian or controller who can force people to believe. He delivers the message; the choice belongs to each individual. This removes any excuse that people were forced or did not have freedom to choose."
  },
  105: {
    "And so We vary our signs to the extent that they will say, \"You have studied ˹previous scriptures˺,\"": "Allah presents His signs in various forms—logical arguments, historical accounts, descriptions of nature, warnings, and promises. This variety is so comprehensive that some accusers claim the Prophet must have studied previous scriptures or learned from others. This accusation itself is a testament to the Quran's richness. In reality, the Prophet was unlettered (ummi) and had no access to such learning.",
    "and We make this ˹Quran˺ clear for people who know": "The true purpose of varying the signs is to make the message clear for those who have knowledge and understanding. Those who sincerely seek truth will find the Quran's explanations comprehensive and illuminating. The variety is a mercy for the seeker, even if it becomes a source of false accusations by the denier."
  },
  106: {
    "˹O Prophet!˺ Follow what is revealed to you from your Lord": "The Prophet receives a direct command to follow the revelation—the Quran. His guidance comes only from Allah, not from human opinion, cultural tradition, or personal desire. This instruction applies to all believers as well: our standard for life must be divine revelation.",
    "—there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him—": "The foundation of this guidance is tawheed: there is no deity deserving of worship except Allah. This declaration is the essence of the message and must be the core of the Prophet's life and teaching.",
    "and turn away from the polytheists": "The Prophet is told to turn away from the polytheists—not to be harsh or aggressive, but to not let their objections, arguments, or pressure divert him from his mission. He should not waste energy trying to please those committed to falsehood. This is strategic, not dismissive—focus on those who will respond."
  },
  107: {
    "Had Allah willed, they would not have been polytheists": "If Allah had wanted, He could have created all humans as believers with no choice in the matter. But He chose to give free will, making faith meaningful and the test of life real. The existence of polytheists is within Allah's will in the sense that He allows it, though He does not approve of it.",
    "We have not appointed you as their keeper, nor are you their maintainer": "Again, the Prophet's role is clarified: he is not responsible for making people believe, nor is he in charge of their affairs. He cannot control their hearts or force their submission. His job is to convey; the results are in Allah's hands. This should relieve any prophet or caller to Islam from feeling personally responsible for others' rejection."
  },
  108: {
    "˹O believers!˺ Do not insult what they invoke besides Allah": "Muslims are prohibited from insulting or cursing the idols and false gods that polytheists worship. This might seem surprising—why protect false deities? But the wisdom becomes clear in the next phrase.",
    "or they will insult Allah spitefully out of ignorance": "If Muslims insult their idols, the polytheists will retaliate by insulting Allah. Out of spite and ignorance, they would speak against the true God. This would be a greater evil than the satisfaction of insulting worthless idols. The principle here is profound: do not do something that leads to a greater harm, even if the action itself seems justified. This is a foundation of Islamic ethics—considering consequences.",
    "This is how We have made each people's deeds appealing to them": "Every group finds its own practices attractive. The polytheists genuinely love their idols and rituals; they are not merely pretending. This attachment, though misguided, is real to them. Understanding this helps explain why they react so defensively when their beliefs are attacked.",
    "Then to their Lord is their return, and He will inform them of what they used to do": "Ultimately, everyone returns to Allah for judgment. He will inform each person and group exactly what they did and settle all matters with perfect justice. The believers should leave the final judgment to Allah rather than escalating conflicts through insults."
  },
  109: {
    "They swear by Allah their most solemn oaths that if a sign were to come to them, they would certainly believe in it": "The disbelievers made emphatic oaths, swearing by Allah Himself, that they would believe if only they could see a specific miracle. They seemed sincere in this promise, and some Muslims might have hoped that sending such a sign would lead to their conversion.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Signs are only with Allah.\"": "The Prophet is instructed to clarify that he does not control miracles—they come only from Allah according to His wisdom. The Prophet cannot produce signs on demand as if performing tricks.",
    "What will make you ˹believers˺ realize that even if a sign were to come to them, they still would not believe?": "This question is addressed to the believers who might have been hopeful about the disbelievers' promise. Allah warns them: do not be deceived. Even if the requested sign came, these people would not believe. Their problem is not lack of evidence but hardness of heart. History proved this—they witnessed many signs yet remained in disbelief."
  },
  110: {
    "We turn their hearts and eyes away ˹from the truth˺ as they refused to believe at first": "Allah explains a divine principle: when people persistently reject truth, Allah turns their hearts and eyes away from guidance. This is not arbitrary punishment but a consequence of their initial rejection. They chose blindness first, so Allah confirms them in their choice. The more they reject, the harder it becomes to accept.",
    "leaving them to wander blindly in their defiance": "They are left in their transgression (tughyan), wandering without direction. This is a frightening state—spiritually lost, unable to find the way out because they repeatedly refused to take it when it was offered."
  },
  111: {
    "Even if We had sent them the angels, made the dead speak to them, and assembled before their own eyes every sign ˹they demanded˺": "Allah presents a hypothetical: even if angels descended visibly, even if dead people came back to life and spoke to them, even if every possible sign they could imagine appeared before their eyes—they still would not believe.",
    "they still would not have believed—unless Allah so willed": "The only way they would believe is if Allah willed guidance for them. And Allah's will to guide is connected to their own sincerity and effort. Since they have none, the guidance does not come. This shows the futility of demanding more signs when the heart is corrupt.",
    "But most of them are ignorant ˹of this˺": "Most people do not understand this reality. They think belief is simply about seeing enough evidence. But belief requires a willing heart, and no amount of external evidence can substitute for internal readiness."
  },
  112: {
    "And so We have made for every prophet enemies—devilish humans and jinn": "This reveals a consistent pattern: every prophet had enemies from both human devils and jinn devils. Not all enemies of truth are supernatural; many are human beings who have embraced evil so completely that they earn the description of \"devils.\" This normalizes opposition for the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him)—he is not alone in facing enemies.",
    "—whispering to one another with elegant words of deception": "These devils communicate with each other, passing along sophisticated, beautifully packaged falsehoods. Their words are attractive on the surface (zukhruf—adorned, decorated) but deceptive at their core. This is how evil often operates: with eloquent arguments, appealing rhetoric, and persuasive presentation that conceals its poisonous content.",
    "Had it been your Lord's Will, they would not have done such a thing": "Allah could have prevented all this opposition, but He allows it as part of the test. The existence of enemies is within His will, though He does not approve of their actions. This is comfort for the Prophet: the opposition is not a sign of failure but part of the divine plan.",
    "So leave them and their deceit": "The Prophet is advised to leave these enemies to their fabrications. Do not be consumed by their plots or distracted by their deceptions. Focus on the mission and let Allah deal with them in His way and time."
  },
  113: {
    "so that the hearts of those who disbelieve in the Hereafter may be receptive to it": "The elegant deceptions of devils find willing audiences—specifically those who deny the Hereafter. People who do not believe in accountability are naturally attracted to falsehood because it removes responsibility. Their hearts incline toward these lies.",
    "be pleased with it": "Beyond mere acceptance, they actually become pleased with the falsehood. They find it comfortable, reassuring, and satisfying. It tells them what they want to hear—that there are no consequences, no judgment, no need to change.",
    "and be persistent in their evil pursuits": "This acceptance leads to action—they continue committing sins and transgressions. The cycle is complete: beautiful lies reach willing hearts, create false comfort, and result in persistent wrongdoing. This is why falsehood is so dangerous—it is a complete system of deception."
  },
  114: {
    "˹Say, O Prophet,˺ \"Should I seek a judge other than Allah while He is the One Who has revealed for you the Book ˹with the truth˺ perfectly explained?\"": "The Prophet asks rhetorically: why would he seek any authority other than Allah as a judge in matters of truth and religion? Allah has revealed the Quran, which is mufassal—detailed and clear in its explanations. It addresses beliefs, ethics, laws, and guidance comprehensively. To seek another judge would be to suggest the Quran is insufficient—an absurd proposition.",
    "Those who were given the Scripture know that it has been revealed ˹to you˺ from your Lord in truth": "The scholars among the Jews and Christians who were honest could recognize that the Quran came from Allah. It matched the description of the final revelation in their own scriptures. Abdullah ibn Salam, a Jewish rabbi, said he recognized Muhammad as clearly as he recognized his own son. Their knowledge testifies to the Quran's truth.",
    "So do not be one of those who doubt": "This is a strong encouragement to the Prophet and believers: do not let the arguments of opponents create doubt. The evidence is clear, the truth is established, and certainty should be firm."
  },
  115: {
    "The Word of your Lord has been perfected in truth and justice": "Allah's word—the Quran—is complete and perfect in two essential qualities: truth (sidq) in what it reports about past, present, and future; and justice (adl) in its commands and prohibitions. Nothing it says is false, and nothing it commands is unfair. This is the standard by which all other claims should be measured.",
    "None can change His Words": "The Quran is protected from alteration. Unlike previous scriptures that were corrupted over time, Allah's final word will remain unchanged. This is a divine promise fulfilled—the Quran today is exactly as it was revealed 1400 years ago, letter for letter.",
    "And He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing": "Allah hears all that is said about His book—the acceptance and the rejection, the respect and the mockery—and He knows everyone's intentions. This is both a comfort to believers and a warning to those who tamper with or reject His words."
  },
  116: {
    "˹O Prophet!˺ If you were to obey most of those on earth, they would lead you away from Allah's Way": "This is a powerful reminder that truth is not determined by majority vote. If one followed what most people on earth believe and do, they would be led astray from Allah's path. The majority of humanity, throughout history, has been upon misguidance. This should not shake a believer's confidence in Islam, even when they are a minority.",
    "They follow nothing but assumptions": "The majority bases their beliefs on conjecture (dhann)—assumptions, guesses, inherited traditions, and unfounded opinions. They lack certain knowledge from divine revelation. Their confidence is misplaced because it rests on speculation rather than truth.",
    "and do nothing but lie": "Their claims are ultimately lies—not necessarily intentional in every case, but objectively false. They speak about religion, about God, about the afterlife without knowledge, and thus produce falsehood."
  },
  117: {
    "Indeed, your Lord knows best who has strayed from His Way and who is ˹rightly˺ guided": "Allah has perfect knowledge of who is guided and who is astray. Human judgments can be wrong—someone might appear religious but have a corrupt heart, or seem unlikely but be sincerely seeking truth. Allah knows the reality, and His judgment is what matters."
  },
  118: {
    "So eat only of what is slaughtered in Allah's Name if you truly believe in His revelations": "This verse establishes a fundamental rule: Muslims should eat meat that has been slaughtered with Allah's name mentioned over it. This practice distinguishes lawful (halal) meat from unlawful (haram) meat. Mentioning Allah's name acknowledges that we take the animal's life by His permission for His sake. Belief in Allah's revelations necessitates following His commands, including this dietary law."
  },
  119: {
    "Why should you not eat of what is slaughtered in Allah's Name": "This rhetorical question challenges any hesitation: what reason could there possibly be to avoid eating properly slaughtered meat? It is lawful, pure, and permitted by Allah Himself.",
    "when He has already explained to you what He has forbidden to you": "Allah has clearly detailed what is prohibited (carrion, blood, pork, etc. as mentioned in other verses). Everything else is permissible. The forbidden items are specific and limited; the lawful is vast.",
    "—except when compelled by necessity?": "Even the prohibited becomes temporarily permissible in cases of genuine necessity—such as starvation when no lawful food is available. This shows Islam's practicality and concern for preserving life.",
    "Many ˹deviants˺ certainly mislead others by their whims out of ignorance": "Some people make things unlawful that Allah made lawful, or permit things Allah prohibited, based on their own desires and without knowledge. They mislead others through these innovations.",
    "Surely your Lord knows the transgressors best": "Allah knows exactly who transgresses His limits—whether by making lawful things forbidden or by consuming what He prohibited. Nothing escapes His knowledge."
  },
  120: {
    "Shun all sin—open and secret": "Muslims must avoid sins that are done publicly and those done privately. Islam is concerned with both external behavior and internal state. A person might avoid public sins for reputation while indulging in private sins, thinking no one sees. But Allah sees everything, and both types of sin are prohibited.",
    "Indeed, those who commit sin will be punished for what they earn": "Sinners will face consequences for their sins—they \"earn\" punishment through their actions. This establishes individual accountability and should motivate believers to avoid all sins, regardless of who might or might not be watching."
  },
  121: {
    "Do not eat of what is not slaughtered in Allah's Name": "This is a clear prohibition: do not consume meat over which Allah's name was not mentioned at slaughter. This includes meat slaughtered for idols or in the name of other deities.",
    "For that would certainly be ˹an act of˺ disobedience": "Eating such meat is fisq—sinful disobedience, a departure from Allah's commands. It is not merely a matter of preference but a religious transgression.",
    "Surely the devils whisper to their ˹human˺ associates to argue with you": "Satan and his followers inspire arguments to confuse Muslims about these laws. They might argue: \"The animal died anyway, what difference does it make who slaughtered it?\" or \"All food is from Allah.\" These are deceptive arguments meant to normalize the forbidden.",
    "If you were to obey them, then you ˹too˺ would be polytheists": "This is a severe warning: following Satan and his allies in making lawful what Allah prohibited is a form of polytheism. It means taking them as legislators alongside Allah—giving them authority that belongs only to Him. This shows how seriously Islam takes the matter of halal and haram."
  },
  122: {
    "Can those who had been dead, to whom We gave life and a light with which they can walk among people": "This powerful metaphor describes the believer: once spiritually dead in disbelief and ignorance, Allah gave them life through faith and a light (the Quran and guidance) by which they navigate through humanity. They see clearly where others stumble. This light illuminates truth from falsehood, right from wrong.",
    "be compared to those in complete darkness from which they can never emerge?": "In contrast, the disbeliever is trapped in layers of darkness—the darkness of disbelief, ignorance, misguidance, and sin. They cannot find their way out because they refuse the light offered to them. How can these two be equal? The answer is obvious: they cannot.",
    "That is how the misdeeds of the disbelievers have been made appealing to them": "The disbelievers find their own sins attractive. Their wrongdoing seems good to them—this is part of their punishment. When someone persistently rejects truth, they lose the ability to see their own errors clearly."
  },
  123: {
    "And so We have placed in every society the most wicked to conspire in it": "In every city and society throughout history, there have been leading criminals who plot against truth and its followers. This is a pattern Allah has allowed as part of the test. These powerful, wicked people use their influence to oppose prophets and believers.",
    "Yet they plot only against themselves, but they fail to perceive it": "Their conspiracies ultimately harm only themselves. They think they are undermining the believers, but they are actually accumulating sins, inviting punishment, and ensuring their own destruction. They are blind to this self-harm, which makes their situation even more tragic."
  },
  124: {
    "Whenever a sign comes to them, they say, \"We will never believe until we receive what Allah's messengers received.\"": "Some arrogant people demanded that they themselves receive revelation and prophethood before they would believe. They essentially said: \"Why should Muhammad receive revelation and not us? We will not follow him until we get the same.\" This reflects extreme arrogance—expecting to dictate to Allah whom He should choose as messengers.",
    "Allah knows best where to place His message": "Allah alone decides who receives prophethood. He knows who is worthy, who can carry the burden, and who will fulfill the mission. Humans cannot demand this honor; it is purely Allah's choice based on His perfect knowledge.",
    "The wicked will soon be overwhelmed by humiliation from Allah and a severe punishment for their evil plots": "These arrogant criminals will face two things: humiliation (the opposite of the honor they sought) and severe punishment for their plotting. Their schemes against the Prophet and the message will bring them nothing but disgrace and suffering."
  },
  125: {
    "Whoever Allah wills to guide, He opens their heart to Islam": "When Allah wants to guide someone, He expands their chest—making their heart receptive, comfortable, and at peace with Islam. They find faith easy to accept, worship pleasant to perform, and obedience natural. This is Allah's gift to those He chooses to guide. The Prophet (peace be upon him) was asked about this expansion, and he said it includes light entering the heart, the chest becoming spacious, disinterest in the deceptive world, turning toward the eternal abode, and preparing for death before it arrives (Ibn Kathir).",
    "But whoever He wills to leave astray, He makes their chest tight and constricted as if they were climbing up into the sky": "For those Allah leaves in misguidance, their chest becomes extremely tight and constricted. The idea of Islam causes them discomfort, anxiety, and distress—like the difficulty of breathing when climbing to high altitudes where oxygen is thin. This physical metaphor captures the spiritual suffocation of the one whose heart rejects truth.",
    "This is how Allah dooms those who disbelieve": "This tightness and spiritual suffocation is Allah's way of placing punishment (rijs—filth, impurity) upon the disbelievers. Their rejection of faith comes with consequences even in this life: an uneasy heart, spiritual emptiness, and inner turmoil despite any external success they might have."
  },
  126: {
    "That is your Lord's Path—perfectly straight": "Islam is the straight path (sirat al-mustaqim)—direct, without deviations, leading clearly to Allah and Paradise. This is not one path among many equal options; it is the path established by the Lord of the universe.",
    "We have already made the signs clear to those who are mindful": "Allah has explained His signs in detail for those who take heed and remember. The signs are available; the explanations are clear. What remains is for individuals to pay attention and act upon what they learn."
  },
  127: {
    "They will have the Home of Peace with their Lord": "The believers who follow this straight path will receive \"Dar as-Salaam\"—the Home of Peace, which is Paradise. It is called this because it is free from all disturbance, harm, grief, and imperfection. Peace permeates every aspect of that eternal abode. And it is \"with their Lord\"—the greatest honor possible.",
    "Who will be their Guardian because of what they used to do": "Allah will be their Wali—their protector, guardian, and friend—as a reward for their righteous deeds. The relationship of loyalty between Allah and the believers, which began in this world through faith and obedience, continues and flourishes eternally in Paradise. This is the beautiful outcome for those who chose to believe and act righteously."
  },
  128: {
    "˹Consider˺ the Day He will gather them ˹all˺ together and say, \"O assembly of jinn! You misled humans in great numbers.\"": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will gather both jinn and humans together. He will address the jinn directly, accusing them of having misled vast numbers of human beings. The jinn—particularly the devils among them—spent their existence whispering to humans, tempting them to sin, and leading them away from guidance. The word 'istakthartum' (you took many) indicates the sheer scale of their corruption.",
    "And their human associates will say, \"Our Lord! We benefited from each other's company,\"": "The humans who followed the jinn will speak up, acknowledging that there was mutual benefit. The jinn benefited by fulfilling their mission of misguidance, while humans benefited by having their desires encouraged and their sins made appealing. Some scholars also mention that certain humans sought help from jinn for worldly gains—power, knowledge, or forbidden pleasures. This partnership was built on mutual corruption.",
    "\"but now we have reached the term which You appointed for us.\"": "The humans acknowledge that their time has run out. The deadline Allah set—death and then judgment—has arrived. There is no more time for excuses, repentance, or escape. The period of testing is over, and now comes the reckoning.",
    "˹Then˺ He will say, \"The Fire is your home, yours to stay in forever, except whoever Allah wills to spare.\"": "Allah pronounces their sentence: Hell is their permanent abode. The phrase 'except whoever Allah wills' shows that ultimate judgment belongs to Allah alone. Some scholars say this refers to those who will eventually be removed from Hell after serving their term (sinful Muslims), while others say it emphasizes Allah's absolute authority over all outcomes.",
    "Surely your Lord is All-Wise, All-Knowing": "The judgment is based on perfect wisdom and complete knowledge. Allah knows exactly who deserves what, and His decisions are based on that perfect understanding. There is no error or injustice in His rulings."
  },
  129: {
    "This is how We make the wrongdoers ˹destructive˺ allies of one another because of their misdeeds": "Allah explains a divine principle: wrongdoers become allies of one another as a consequence of their sins. Evil attracts evil. Those who sin find companions in sin, and together they lead each other deeper into destruction. The devils are assigned to those who deserve them, and corrupt humans find each other. This alliance, which seems beneficial in this world, becomes the source of mutual blame and shared punishment in the Hereafter. Your company in sin becomes your company in punishment."
  },
  130: {
    "˹Allah will ask,˺ \"O assembly of jinn and humans! Did messengers not come from among you, proclaiming My revelations and warning you of the coming of this Day of yours?\"": "Allah directly questions both species: Were you not warned? Messengers came to humanity, and according to scholars, the jinn either had their own messengers or heard the human prophets' message (as mentioned in Surah Al-Jinn where jinn listened to the Prophet's recitation). Either way, the message reached them. The question is rhetorical—Allah already knows the answer, but He makes them acknowledge it themselves.",
    "They will say, \"We confess against ourselves!\"": "There will be no denial on that Day. The jinn and humans will testify against themselves, admitting their guilt. The overwhelming reality of standing before Allah, with all deeds exposed, leaves no room for lies. They confess that they received the message and rejected it.",
    "For they have been deluded by ˹their˺ worldly life": "The reason for their rejection is revealed: the temporary attractions of this world deceived them. They were so absorbed in pursuing pleasures, wealth, status, and comfort that they neglected the eternal consequences. The dunya (worldly life) is described as 'ghuroor'—a deception that looked real but was ultimately an illusion.",
    "And they will testify against themselves that they were disbelievers": "Their final testimony confirms their disbelief. They cannot claim innocence, ignorance, or that they were not given a fair chance. They admit they knew but chose to reject. This testimony seals their fate."
  },
  131: {
    "This ˹sending of the messengers˺ is because your Lord would never destroy a society for their wrongdoing while its people are unaware ˹of the truth˺": "This verse establishes a fundamental principle of divine justice: Allah never punishes a people without first sending them clear guidance. No nation is destroyed for wrongdoing until after messengers have come to them and made the truth clear. If people are genuinely unaware, they are not punished for that unawareness. This shows Allah's perfect fairness—punishment only comes after the evidence is established and rejected."
  },
  132: {
    "They will each be assigned ranks according to their deeds": "Both the righteous and the wicked will receive different levels based on their actions. Among believers, some will have higher stations in Paradise based on their deeds. Among disbelievers, some will have worse positions in Hell based on the severity of their crimes. Nothing is flattened into a single category—every deed, large and small, affects one's rank.",
    "And your Lord is not unaware of what they do": "Allah sees everything. No deed—public or private, significant or seemingly insignificant—escapes His knowledge. This is both a warning to evildoers and a comfort to the righteous: your good deeds, even those no one else sees, are fully known and will be rewarded accordingly."
  },
  133: {
    "Your Lord is the Self-Sufficient, Full of Mercy": "Allah is Al-Ghani—completely free of any need from His creation. He does not need our worship, obedience, or anything else. At the same time, He is 'Full of Mercy' (Dhu ar-Rahmah)—despite not needing us, He showers us with mercy. This combination humbles the arrogant and gives hope to the humble.",
    "If He wills, He can do away with you and replace you with whoever He wills": "Allah is not dependent on this particular generation of humans. If He wanted, He could remove the current people and bring entirely new creations in their place. This is not an empty threat—it highlights human insignificance before Allah's power while also being a warning to those who persist in disobedience.",
    "just as He produced you from the offspring of other people": "We ourselves are the replacements of those who came before us. Previous nations lived, died, and were succeeded by us. Just as easily, we could be removed and replaced. This historical reality should inspire humility and urgency in following guidance."
  },
  134: {
    "Indeed, what you have been promised will certainly come to pass": "The Day of Judgment, the resurrection, the reckoning—everything the Prophet warned about will definitely happen. There is no doubt, no possibility of it being cancelled or delayed indefinitely. It is coming with absolute certainty.",
    "And you will have no escape": "When that Day arrives, no one will be able to escape it. There will be no hiding place, no bribe that works, no powerful ally who can help. Everyone will face it, and everyone will be held accountable."
  },
  135: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O my people! Persist in your ways, for I ˹too˺ will persist in mine\"": "This is a powerful statement of resolve. The Prophet tells his people: if you insist on your path of disbelief, then continue on it, and I will continue on my path of truth and obedience to Allah. This is not giving up on them but rather a challenge—let time and outcome show who is right.",
    "You will soon know who will fare best in the end": "The truth will become clear eventually. Either in this life through the victory of Islam and the defeat of its enemies, or in the Hereafter when judgment is rendered. The 'soon' emphasizes that from Allah's perspective and in terms of eternity, the reckoning is near.",
    "Indeed, the wrongdoers will never succeed": "This is a categorical statement: ultimate success will never belong to those who persist in wrongdoing. They may appear successful temporarily—with wealth, power, and influence—but true, lasting success is only for the righteous. The wrongdoers' apparent success is merely a delay before their inevitable failure."
  },
  136: {
    "The pagans set aside for Allah a share of the crops and cattle He created, saying, \"This ˹portion˺ is for Allah,\" so they claim, \"and this ˹one˺ for our associate-gods.\"": "The pre-Islamic Arabs would divide their harvests and livestock, allocating portions to Allah and portions to their idols. This itself was wrong—making their invented gods partners with Allah in receiving offerings from His creation.",
    "Yet the portion of their associate-gods is not shared with Allah while Allah's portion is shared with their associate-gods": "Their practice was even more unjust: if the portion for the idols was accidentally mixed with Allah's portion, they would restore the idols' share. But if Allah's portion was mixed with the idols' portion, they would leave it for the idols. They actually gave preference to their invented gods over Allah!",
    "What unfair judgment!": "Allah condemns this practice as evil and unjust. They claimed to honor Allah but actually prioritized their false gods. This exposes the inconsistency and absurdity of their polytheism—even by their own flawed standards, they were being unfair."
  },
  137: {
    "Likewise, the pagans' evil associates have made it appealing to them to kill their own children": "The devils among jinn and humans made infanticide seem acceptable, even noble, to many polytheists. Some killed daughters out of fear of shame or poverty. Others sacrificed children to idols. These practices—unthinkable to natural human compassion—were made to seem normal through satanic influence.",
    "—only leading to their destruction as well as confusion in their faith": "This practice led to two outcomes: their own destruction (both in this life through declining population and in the Hereafter through punishment) and confusion in their religion. Their beliefs became increasingly corrupted and contradictory because they were built on such horrific foundations.",
    "Had it been Allah's Will, they would not have done such a thing": "Allah could have prevented all this, but He allows human free will and the consequences that follow. The existence of such evils is within Allah's will in the sense that He permits it, but He certainly does not approve of it.",
    "So leave them and their falsehood": "The Prophet is told to distance himself from their fabricated lies. He has delivered the message; now let them bear the consequences of their inventions. This provides emotional relief—the Prophet should not carry the burden of their persistent rejection."
  },
  138: {
    "They say, \"These cattle and crops are reserved—none may eat them except those we permit,\" so they claim": "The pagans invented arbitrary rules about which animals and crops could be eaten and by whom. These were not divine commands but human inventions given religious authority. They restricted access to certain foods for no legitimate reason.",
    "Some other cattle are exempted from labour and others are not slaughtered in Allah's Name": "They made up various categories: some animals were forbidden to be ridden or used for work; others were forbidden to have Allah's name mentioned over them at slaughter—instead they were slaughtered for idols. All of these rules were fabrications with no basis in divine guidance.",
    "—falsely attributing lies to Him. He will repay them for their lies": "The worst aspect was claiming these rules came from Allah when they were purely human inventions. Lying about what Allah commanded is among the gravest sins. Allah promises to repay them for these fabrications—they will face consequences for every false claim they made in His name."
  },
  139: {
    "They ˹also˺ say, \"The offspring of this cattle is reserved for our males and forbidden to our females\"": "Another invented rule: the offspring of certain animals was permitted exclusively for men while women were prohibited from consuming it. This discrimination had no divine basis—it was pure human invention designed to maintain male privilege under the guise of religion.",
    "\"but if it is stillborn, they may all share it\"": "Strangely, if the offspring was stillborn (carrion), then suddenly women were allowed to share it. The illogic is apparent: the better food is restricted while the inferior, even impure food is shared. This inconsistency further exposes the arbitrariness of their rules.",
    "He will repay them for their falsehood": "Once again, Allah promises recompense for these lies. Every false rule they attributed to Him is recorded and will be addressed.",
    "Surely He is All-Wise, All-Knowing": "Allah's wisdom and knowledge are perfect. His actual laws make sense and are based on wisdom, unlike the arbitrary, contradictory rules humans invent. And He knows exactly who invented what lies."
  },
  140: {
    "Lost indeed are those who have murdered their own children foolishly out of ignorance": "The verdict is pronounced: these people have utterly lost. They killed their own children—an act of foolishness (safahan) driven by ignorance. They thought they were acting wisely (avoiding poverty, shame, or pleasing gods) but were actually committing the worst possible crime against their own families.",
    "and have forbidden what Allah has provided for them—falsely attributing lies to Allah": "Adding to their crimes, they made lawful things unlawful, prohibiting foods that Allah had provided. They claimed divine authority for rules Allah never authorized. This combination of murder and religious fabrication represents a profound loss of both humanity and faith.",
    "They have certainly strayed and are not ˹rightly˺ guided": "The final assessment: they are lost, astray, completely off the path. And they were never actually guided—despite their claims to religious knowledge, they were always wandering in darkness of their own making."
  },
  141: {
    "He is the One Who produces gardens—both cultivated and wild—and palm trees, crops of different flavours, olives, and pomegranates—similar ˹in shape˺, but dissimilar ˹in taste˺": "Allah contrasts the pagans' false rules with the reality of His creation. He produces all kinds of gardens: some trellised (cultivated on supports) and some growing freely without support. He creates palm trees, various crops with different tastes, olives, and pomegranates. Some look similar but taste different—all this diversity comes from the same water and soil, demonstrating Allah's creative power.",
    "Eat from the fruit they bear": "The command is clear: eat from these fruits. Allah has made them lawful and provided them for human consumption. The pagans' arbitrary restrictions were never divine—Allah's actual command is to enjoy His provisions.",
    "and pay the dues at harvest": "From Allah's bounty comes responsibility. At harvest time, give what is due—charity, alms, zakah on agricultural produce. The scholars differ on whether this specifically refers to obligatory zakah or general charity, but the principle is clear: share Allah's bounty with others.",
    "but do not waste. Surely He does not like the wasteful": "Moderation is commanded. Do not be excessive in eating, in spending, or in charity to the point where you harm yourself or your dependents. Balance is the key. Allah does not love those who waste—extravagance and excess are displeasing to Him."
  },
  142: {
    "Some cattle are fit for labour, others are too small": "Allah created different types of cattle: large ones useful for carrying loads and working, and smaller ones (or young ones) used for other purposes like wool or meat. All are from Allah's provision.",
    "Eat of what Allah has provided for you": "Again, the command to eat from Allah's provision is emphasized. The cattle He created are lawful—do not invent restrictions that Allah never commanded.",
    "and do not follow Satan's footsteps": "The arbitrary prohibitions invented by the pagans were Satan's influence. Following him happens step by step—first a small deviation, then another, until one is completely lost. The warning is to avoid even the first step.",
    "Certainly, he is your sworn enemy": "Satan's enmity is not hidden or subtle—it is clear (mubeen). He openly declared war on humanity from the time of Adam. Anyone who recognizes this obvious enmity would never follow him."
  },
  143: {
    "˹Allah has created˺ four pairs: a pair of sheep and a pair of goats": "Allah created eight animals in pairs: two sheep (male and female) and two goats (male and female). This is the first set of four pairs.",
    "—ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Has He forbidden ˹to you˺ the two males or the two females or what is in the wombs of the two females?": "The Prophet is instructed to challenge their arbitrary rules with logic. If they claim certain animals are forbidden, ask them: Is it specifically the males that are forbidden? Or the females? Or what the females carry in their wombs? Their rules made no logical sense and had no divine basis.",
    "Tell me with knowledge, if what you say is true.\"": "This demands evidence. If they truly received these rules from Allah, they should be able to explain them with knowledge. But they cannot, because these were human inventions."
  },
  144: {
    "and a pair of camels and a pair of oxen": "The second set of four pairs: two camels (male and female) and two cattle (male and female). All eight animals in four pairs are lawful.",
    "Ask ˹them˺, \"Has He forbidden ˹to you˺ the two males or the two females or what is in the wombs of the two females?": "The same logical challenge is repeated for camels and cattle. Which part exactly did Allah forbid? They cannot answer because there was no divine prohibition.",
    "Or were you present when Allah gave you this commandment?\"": "This is cutting sarcasm: Were you there when Allah supposedly gave these commands? Did you witness the revelation? Of course not—they invented these rules themselves.",
    "Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against Allah to mislead others without ˹any˺ knowledge?": "The rhetorical question establishes that the greatest wrongdoers are those who invent lies about Allah and use those lies to misguide others—all without any actual knowledge. This is a severe accusation against the pagan leaders who created these false religious rules.",
    "Surely Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people": "Those who persist in such wrongdoing—inventing lies about Allah—will not receive guidance. They have chosen to misguide others, so Allah leaves them in their misguidance."
  },
  145: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"I do not find in what has been revealed to me anything forbidden to eat except carrion": "The Prophet is commanded to clarify what is actually prohibited. The first category is carrion (maytah)—animals that died without proper slaughter. This includes animals that died of disease, were strangled, beaten to death, fell from heights, were gored, or were partially eaten by predators.",
    "running blood": "The second category is flowing blood (dam masfuh)—blood that pours out when an animal is slaughtered. This does not include blood that remains in the meat after proper draining, nor organs like the liver and spleen.",
    "swine—which is impure—": "The third category is pork in all its forms. It is described as 'rijs' (impure/filth). The entire pig is forbidden—its meat, fat, and all derivatives. Modern science has discovered various health concerns with pork, confirming the wisdom of this prohibition.",
    "or a sinful offering in the name of any other than Allah": "The fourth category is meat slaughtered in the name of any deity other than Allah. This is 'fisq' (sinful disobedience) because it involves associating partners with Allah in the most fundamental act of taking a life.",
    "But if someone is compelled by necessity—neither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need—then surely your Lord is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "In cases of genuine necessity—starvation with no lawful food available—even these prohibited items become temporarily permissible. However, the person must not desire the forbidden food or exceed the minimum needed to survive. Allah's forgiveness and mercy cover those who are truly compelled by circumstances beyond their control."
  },
  146: {
    "For those who are Jewish, We forbade every animal with undivided hoofs": "The Jews had additional dietary restrictions not required of Muslims. Animals without split hooves (like rabbits, camels, and various birds) were forbidden to them.",
    "and the fat of oxen and sheep except what is joined to their backs or intestines or mixed with bone": "The fat of cattle and sheep was also forbidden to Jews, except the fat attached to the back, intestines, or mixed with bone. This was a specific, detailed restriction.",
    "In this way We rewarded them for their violations": "These extra restrictions were not arbitrary cruelty but a punishment for their previous rebellions and violations of Allah's commands. Their disobedience led to a stricter law. This shows that sin can result in loss of blessings and increased burdens.",
    "And We are certainly truthful": "Allah confirms the truth of this account. The Jews knew these were their restrictions, and Allah explains their origin—something they may have forgotten or misrepresented over time."
  },
  147: {
    "But if they deny you ˹O Prophet˺, say, \"Your Lord is infinite in mercy\"": "If they reject this explanation, the Prophet should remind them that Allah's mercy is vast. This is both a comfort and an invitation—despite their denial, Allah's mercy remains open to those who repent.",
    "yet His punishment will not be averted from the wicked people": "However, Allah's mercy does not negate His justice. For those who persist in wickedness, punishment will not be turned away. They cannot escape accountability simply because Allah is merciful. Mercy is for those who seek it; punishment is for those who reject it."
  },
  148: {
    "The polytheists will argue, \"Had it been Allah's Will, neither we nor our forefathers would have associated others with Him ˹in worship˺ or made anything unlawful.\"": "This is a common excuse: if Allah did not want us to be polytheists, He would have stopped us. They use divine will as justification for their sins—essentially claiming Allah approved of their behavior because He allowed it to happen.",
    "Likewise, those before them rejected the truth until they tasted Our punishment": "This excuse is not new. Previous nations made the same argument until Allah's punishment came upon them. Their argument did not save them from consequences.",
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Do you have any knowledge that you can produce for us?\"": "Challenge them to present evidence for their claims. If Allah truly commanded or approved of their polytheism and fabricated prohibitions, they should be able to prove it.",
    "Surely you follow nothing but ˹false˺ assumptions and you do nothing but lie": "Their argument has no foundation in knowledge—only assumptions (dhann) and lies (khars). They guess about divine matters and lie about what Allah commanded."
  },
  149: {
    "Say, \"Allah has the most conclusive argument\"": "Allah's argument is complete and irrefutable (al-hujjah al-balighah). He sent messengers, revealed scriptures, established clear signs—the evidence is overwhelming. Humans have no excuse.",
    "Had it been His Will, He would have easily imposed guidance upon all of you": "Yes, Allah could have forced everyone to believe—but that would eliminate free will and make the test meaningless. He chose to give guidance while preserving human choice. Their argument misuses the concept of divine will."
  },
  150: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Bring your witnesses who can testify that Allah has forbidden this.\"": "Another challenge: bring witnesses who can confirm that Allah actually prohibited what you claim He prohibited. This demands evidence—divine commands require proof.",
    "If they ˹falsely˺ testify, do not testify with them": "Even if they produce false witnesses, the Prophet should not validate their lies by participating. False testimony about divine law is among the worst sins.",
    "And do not follow the desires of those who deny Our proofs, disbelieve in the Hereafter, and set up equals with their Lord": "Three characteristics disqualify their claims: they deny Allah's signs, reject the afterlife, and commit polytheism. Following such people leads only to destruction. Their 'religious' opinions are worthless because their foundation is corrupt."
  },
  151: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Come! Let me recite to you what your Lord has forbidden to you": "The Prophet is commanded to invite people to hear the actual divine prohibitions—not the fabricated rules of the pagans, but what Allah has truly forbidden. This is an authoritative declaration that replaces all human inventions with genuine divine guidance. The invitation 'Come!' shows openness and eagerness to share the truth.",
    "do not associate others with Him ˹in worship˺": "The first and most fundamental commandment: do not commit shirk. This is the foundation upon which all other commandments rest. Polytheism is the greatest sin because it violates the very purpose of creation—to worship Allah alone. Everything else in religion flows from this principle. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said when asked about the greatest sin: 'To set up rivals with Allah though He alone created you' (Bukhari).",
    "˹Do not fail to˺ honour your parents": "The second commandment concerns parents. The command is for 'ihsan'—excellence and beauty in treatment, going beyond mere obedience to genuine kindness, respect, and care. Parents are mentioned immediately after Allah because they are the means of our existence and our first teachers. The Quran repeatedly links the rights of parents with the rights of Allah.",
    "Do not kill your children for fear of poverty": "The third commandment forbids infanticide motivated by economic fear. Some Arabs would kill their children—especially daughters—fearing they could not provide for them. Allah addresses this fear directly: provision comes from Him, not from human calculation. He provides for both parents and children. This prohibition extends to abortion for economic reasons and reflects the sanctity of innocent life.",
    "We provide for you and for them": "This reassurance removes the excuse of poverty. Allah takes responsibility for provision. Killing children to avoid poverty shows a lack of trust in Allah (tawakkul) and a tragic misunderstanding of how sustenance works. Rizq (provision) is guaranteed by Allah; our job is to trust and make legitimate effort.",
    "Do not come near indecencies, openly or secretly": "The fourth commandment forbids all forms of sexual immorality and shameful acts—whether committed publicly or privately. The phrase 'do not come near' is significant: it prohibits not just the act itself but everything that leads to it. This includes avoiding situations, relationships, and content that could lead to indecency. Both external actions and private sins are covered—Allah sees what is hidden just as He sees what is open.",
    "Do not take a ˹human˺ life—made sacred by Allah—except with ˹legal˺ right": "The fifth commandment protects human life. Allah has made human life sacred (haram)—it cannot be taken without legitimate cause established by Islamic law (such as legal execution for murder, or killing in legitimate warfare). Murder is among the greatest sins after shirk. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'The first matter to be judged between people on the Day of Judgment will be blood (murder)' (Bukhari).",
    "This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will understand": "These five commandments are what Allah actually enjoins—not human fabrications. The purpose is that people might use their intellect ('aql) to understand the wisdom behind these laws and live accordingly."
  },
  152: {
    "And do not come near the wealth of the orphan—unless intending to enhance it—until they attain maturity": "The sixth commandment protects orphans' property. Guardians must not touch an orphan's wealth except in ways that benefit and grow it. This continues until the orphan reaches maturity and can manage their own affairs. Orphans are vulnerable—they have lost their protector—so Allah places extra emphasis on their rights. The guardian's role is trusteeship, not ownership.",
    "Give full measure and weigh with justice": "The seventh commandment concerns honesty in business transactions. When measuring or weighing goods, give full amounts without cheating. This prohibition against fraud extends to all forms of commercial dishonesty. The people of Shu'ayb (peace be upon him) were destroyed partly for this sin of cheating in measurements. Economic justice is a religious obligation.",
    "We never require of any soul more than what it can afford": "Allah, in His mercy, only demands what is within a person's capacity. This applies to the command about fair measurement—do your best to be accurate, and Allah knows human limitations. It also applies to all religious obligations: Allah does not burden people beyond their ability.",
    "Whenever you speak, maintain justice—even regarding a close relative": "The eighth commandment requires truthful, just speech in all circumstances. Whether giving testimony, reporting news, or making judgments, justice must be maintained—even if it goes against your own family members. Tribal loyalty and family bonds cannot override truth and justice. This is one of the hardest tests of integrity.",
    "And fulfil your covenant with Allah": "The ninth commandment is to honor all commitments made with Allah. This includes the covenant of faith itself, specific vows made to Allah, and the general commitment to follow His guidance. Breaking promises to Allah is a severe sin that undermines the foundation of one's relationship with the Creator.",
    "This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will be mindful": "These commandments are reminders (dhikr) to keep people conscious of their obligations. The goal is taqwa—mindfulness of Allah that shapes behavior."
  },
  153: {
    "Indeed, that is My Path—perfectly straight. So follow it": "The tenth commandment: follow Allah's straight path exclusively. This path—defined by the previous commandments and the complete guidance of Islam—is direct, without deviations. It leads straight to Allah's pleasure and Paradise. The command is clear: follow this path.",
    "and do not follow other ways, for they will lead you away from His Way": "Every path other than Allah's leads astray. The Prophet (peace be upon him) once drew a straight line and said 'This is Allah's path,' then drew lines branching off and said 'These are other paths, at the head of each is a devil calling to it' (Ahmad). The plurality of false paths contrasts with the singularity of truth.",
    "This is what He has commanded you, so perhaps you will be conscious ˹of Allah˺": "The ultimate goal of all these commandments is taqwa—consciousness of Allah that permeates every aspect of life. These ten commandments, when followed, develop a person's awareness of Allah and shape them into a righteous servant."
  },
  154: {
    "Additionally, We gave Moses the Scripture, completing the favour upon those who do good": "Allah mentions that He gave Moses (Musa, peace be upon him) the Torah as a completion of His blessings upon those who strove for excellence. The Torah was a comprehensive guidance for the Children of Israel, building upon and completing previous guidance.",
    "detailing everything": "The Torah contained detailed explanations of religious law, ethics, stories of previous peoples, and guidance for all aspects of life that the Israelites needed at that time. Nothing essential was left out.",
    "and as a guide and a mercy": "Like all divine scriptures, the Torah served as guidance (huda) showing the right path, and mercy (rahma) from Allah to His servants. Following it led to success in both worlds.",
    "so perhaps they would be certain of the meeting with their Lord": "The ultimate purpose was to build certainty (yaqeen) in the meeting with Allah—the Day of Judgment. Scripture is meant to prepare people for that inevitable meeting by giving them knowledge and motivation to live righteously."
  },
  155: {
    "This is a blessed Book We have revealed": "The Quran is described as 'mubarak'—full of blessings. It brings blessing to those who recite it, study it, follow it, and teach it. Every interaction with the Quran carries divine blessing. It is the final and most complete revelation from Allah.",
    "So follow it and be mindful ˹of Allah˺, so you may be shown mercy": "Two commands follow: follow the Quran's guidance and maintain taqwa (consciousness of Allah). The result of doing both is receiving Allah's mercy. This is the formula for success: Quran + Taqwa = Mercy."
  },
  156: {
    "You ˹pagans˺ can no longer say, \"Scriptures were only revealed to two groups before us and we were unaware of their teachings.\"": "This verse removes a potential excuse. The Arabs might have claimed that they were at a disadvantage because previous scriptures (Torah and Gospel) were given to Jews and Christians in foreign languages and they had no access to study them. Now, with the Quran revealed in clear Arabic, this excuse is eliminated. The truth has come in their own language."
  },
  157: {
    "Nor can you say, \"If only the Scriptures had been revealed to us, we would have been better guided than they.\"": "Another excuse is blocked: the claim that if they had received scripture directly, they would have followed it better than the Jews and Christians did. This boastful claim is now put to the test.",
    "Now there has come to you from your Lord a clear proof—a guide and mercy": "The test is here. The Quran has arrived—a clear proof (bayyina), guidance, and mercy—directly to the Arabs in their language. Now they must demonstrate whether their claim was genuine or empty boasting.",
    "Who then does more wrong than those who deny Allah's revelations and turn away from them?": "After all excuses are removed, rejection becomes the worst form of wrongdoing. Those who deny and turn away from clear divine signs after receiving them directly have no justification. They are the greatest wrongdoers.",
    "We will reward those who turn away from Our revelations with a dreadful punishment for turning away": "The consequence of turning away from Allah's signs is severe punishment. The repetition of 'turning away' emphasizes that this is a deliberate, conscious rejection—not mere ignorance. Such deliberate rejection deserves the worst punishment."
  },
  158: {
    "Are they awaiting the coming of the angels, or your Lord ˹Himself˺, or some of your Lord's ˹major˺ signs?": "This rhetorical question exposes the disbelievers' delay tactics. What exactly are they waiting for? The angels of death? Allah Himself to appear? Major apocalyptic signs? All of these will come, but when they do, it will be too late.",
    "On the Day your Lord's signs arrive, belief will not benefit those who did not believe earlier": "When the major signs of the Hour appear—such as the sun rising from the west—the door of repentance closes. Faith at that moment is meaningless because the unseen has become seen. The test requires believing before seeing the undeniable proof.",
    "or those who did no good through their faith": "Similarly, someone who claimed to believe but never did any good deeds will not benefit. Faith without action is incomplete. When the signs appear, there is no more time to accumulate good deeds. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said there are three things which, when they occur, faith will not benefit one who did not believe before: the rising of the sun from the west, the Dajjal (Antichrist), and the Beast (Muslim).",
    "Say, \"Keep waiting! We too are waiting.\"": "This is a challenge: if you want to wait until the last moment, go ahead. The believers are also waiting—but they are waiting in a state of preparation, while the disbelievers are waiting in a state of heedlessness. The outcomes of the two waitings will be vastly different."
  },
  159: {
    "Indeed, you ˹O Prophet˺ are not responsible whatsoever for those who have divided their faith and split into sects": "The Prophet is completely disassociated from those who fragment the religion into competing sects and parties. This applies to previous communities like the Jews and Christians who split, and serves as a warning to Muslims not to follow the same path. The unity of the ummah is a divine command, and sectarianism is condemned.",
    "Their judgment rests only with Allah": "Allah will judge between the sects. The Prophet's role is not to settle their disputes or take sides among various deviant groups. Ultimate judgment belongs to Allah alone.",
    "And He will inform them of what they used to do": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will clarify exactly what each sect did—their innovations, their departures from truth, and their responsibility for division. Nothing will be hidden."
  },
  160: {
    "Whoever comes with a good deed will be rewarded tenfold": "This reveals Allah's generous justice. A single good deed is multiplied by ten in reward—and this is the minimum multiplication. For some deeds, the reward can be multiplied by 700 or even more without limit. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah said: 'Every deed of the son of Adam is multiplied for him, a good deed receiving ten times to seven hundred times its like' (Muslim).",
    "But whoever comes with a bad deed will be punished for only one": "In contrast, a sin is repaid with only an equivalent punishment—no multiplication. This shows divine mercy: good is amplified while evil is limited. Even in punishment, Allah is just, not excessive.",
    "None will be wronged": "No one will be treated unjustly. The righteous will receive their full reward (and more), and the sinful will not be punished beyond what they deserve. This perfect balance defines Allah's justice."
  },
  161: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Surely my Lord has guided me to the Straight Path, a perfect way, the faith of Abraham, the upright, who was not one of the polytheists.\"": "The Prophet is commanded to declare his guidance. Allah has led him to the straight path—a complete, upright religion (deen qiyyam) that is the same as Abraham's way. Abraham was a hanif—someone who turned away from all falsehood toward pure monotheism. The Prophet follows this ancient, pure tradition. This also establishes continuity: Islam is not a new invention but the restoration of Abraham's original faith."
  },
  162: {
    "Say, \"Surely my prayer, my worship, my life, and my death are all for Allah—Lord of all worlds.\"": "This is the ultimate declaration of total dedication. Every act of prayer (salah), every act of worship (nusuk—which includes sacrifice and all devotional acts), the entirety of one's life, and even one's death—all are dedicated to Allah alone. There is no compartmentalization: religion is not just for the mosque, but every moment, every action, every breath belongs to Allah. This is the essence of being a Muslim—one who submits completely to Allah."
  },
  163: {
    "He has no partner": "Allah is absolutely unique—no partner in His essence, His attributes, His worship, or His sovereignty. This reaffirms tawheed in the most comprehensive way.",
    "So I am commanded": "This complete dedication is not optional or self-invented—it is what Allah has commanded. The Prophet follows divine instruction, not personal preference.",
    "and so I am the first to submit.\"": "Among his people, the Prophet was the first to submit to this message. He leads by example, being the foremost in obedience to what he calls others toward. 'Muslim' means one who submits, and the Prophet is the exemplary Muslim."
  },
  164: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Should I seek a lord other than Allah while He is the Lord of everything?\"": "This rhetorical question makes an obvious point: why would anyone seek another lord when Allah is already the Lord of everything? All other proposed lords are themselves under Allah's lordship. Seeking them is illogical and futile.",
    "No one will reap except what they sow": "Each soul earns for itself—good or evil. The consequences of a person's actions return to them. You cannot benefit from someone else's good deeds (unless they taught you or you participated), and you cannot be punished for someone else's sins.",
    "No soul burdened with sin will bear the burden of another": "This fundamental principle of Islamic justice states that no one carries the sin of another. Everyone is responsible for their own actions. This contradicts doctrines of inherited sin or vicarious atonement. Each person faces their own reckoning.",
    "Then to your Lord is your return, and He will inform you of your differences": "Ultimately, everyone returns to Allah, and He will clarify all the matters people disputed about in this world—religious questions, sectarian differences, claims and counterclaims. The final truth will be made clear."
  },
  165: {
    "He is the One Who has placed you as successors on earth": "Humans are 'khala'if'—successors or stewards on earth. We inherited the earth from previous generations and will pass it to those who come after. We are caretakers, not owners. This status comes with responsibility: to manage the earth according to Allah's guidance, not our whims.",
    "and elevated some of you in rank over others": "Allah has created diversity in human circumstances—some have more wealth, power, health, or knowledge than others. These differences are not random or unjust; they are part of the divine test.",
    "so He may test you with what He has given you": "The variations in worldly circumstances are tests. The wealthy are tested with their wealth (will they be grateful and charitable?), the poor with their poverty (will they be patient and trust Allah?), the powerful with their power (will they be just?), and the weak with their weakness (will they maintain dignity and faith?). Every blessing and every challenge is part of the examination.",
    "Surely your Lord is swift in punishment": "Those who fail the test—who are ungrateful, unjust, or rebellious—will face quick punishment. Allah's retribution can come suddenly, without warning.",
    "but He is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Yet alongside swift punishment is expansive forgiveness and mercy. Those who repent, who strive despite their failures, who turn back to Allah—they find Him forgiving and merciful. This balance of justice and mercy is the essence of Allah's dealing with His creation. The surah ends on this note of hope: no matter what sins one has committed, Allah's forgiveness is available to those who sincerely seek it."
  }
};